{"title_page": "Maggie and the Ferocious Beast", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Short description|Canadian animated children's television series created by Michael and Betty Paraskevas}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Maggie and the Ferocious Beast\n| image                    = Maggie and the Ferocious Beast Logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Fantasy film|Fantasy]]\n| creator                  = [[Michael Paraskevas]] and [[Betty Paraskevas]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = Gabe Mannes\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Kristen Bone\n* [[Stephen Ouimette]]\n* Michael Caruana\n* [[Julie Lemieux]]\n* [[Adrian Truss]]\n* Tamara Bernier\n* John McGrath\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = TTG Music Lab\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Branton\n* Tony Crea\n* Mike Northcott\n}}\n| country                  = Canada\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 39 (117 segments)\n| list_episodes            = List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist |\n* Michael Hirsh\n* Patrick Loubert\n* Clive A. Smith\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Cynthia Taylor\n* Steve Hodgins\n* Patricia R. Burns (supervising)\n}}\n| editor                   = Stephanie Duncan\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[Nelvana]]\n| distributor              = Nelvana\n| channel                  = [[Teletoon]]\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2001|8|26}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2003|06|09}}\n| website                  = http://www.ferociousbeast.com/\n| production_website       = http://www.nelvana.com/show/119/maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast\n}}\n'''''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast''''' is a Canadian [[Animated series|animated]] [[children's television series]] created by [[Michael Paraskevas|Michael]] and [[Betty Paraskevas]]. The program was based on the 1996 book ''The Ferocious Beast with the Polka-Dot Hide'' and its sequels, all of which were also written by the Paraskevases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parents-choice.org/article.cfm?art_id=330&the_page=editorials|title=Inside Maggie and the Ferocious Beast|work=Parents-Choice.org|publisher=[[Parents' Choice Award|Parents' Choice Foundation]]|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe show began as a series of shorts aired on the Canadian channel [[Teletoon]] in 1998. The first full-length episode premiered on August 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Nelvana's+%22Maggie+and+the+Ferocious+Beast%22+soars+to+a+ferocious+No.+1...-a063944653 |title=Nelvana's \"Maggie and the Ferocious Beast\" soars to a ferocious No. 1 on Nick Jr. - Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref>   \n\nThe series began airing on [[Qubo]] on May 28, 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nA young girl named Maggie creates her own map of an imaginary world known as \"Nowhere Land\" that, in reality, takes the characters nowhere. She imagines that characters Beast and Hamilton Hocks are her friends.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes}}\n{{:List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes}}\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Main===\n* Maggie (voiced by Kristen Bone) is a five-year-old girl (who later turns six years old)  and the human protagonist of the show. She is Hamilton's and Beast's best friend. They both look up to Maggie very much and always turn to her for advice. Maggie is the leader of the group and is always there to be the compassionate voice of reason to her dear friends.\n* The Ferocious Beast (voiced by [[Stephen Ouimette]]) he is very scary or ferocious. However, he can shout louder than anybody. He is a yellow beast, with big red removable spots, and three horns on his head. His favorite catchphrase is \"Great googly moogly!\", which he says several times per episode. In \"Hide And Go Beast\", it is shown that he is allergic to pollen. He is just a big softie, despite his bold appearance. Beast loves pumpkins, which is convenient since there is an impressive pumpkin patch in Nowhere Land. As a matter of fact, Beast loves pretty much any kind of food, including Hamilton's cooking, and is almost always hungry. He even loves baths. Maggie and Hamilton are his best friends. He wears multi-colored galoshes which he pronounces as \"Goo-lashes\". Hamilton always corrects him about the pronunciation, but he does not believe him.\n* Hamilton Hocks (voiced by Michael Caruana) is a pig who can be bossy and quite fussy, but he has a warm heart. He lives inside a portable cardboard box which he loves, is the best cook in Nowhere Land, and is a total clean freak. Hamilton's most prized possessions are his beautiful \"H\" sweater and his cardboard box, which also happens to be his home. Maggie and the Beast are his best friends.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Rudy the Mouse: Rudy is a cheese-loving mouse who lives in a large wheel of cheese in a part of Nowhere Land called Cheese Town. It is revealed in one episode that Rudy's hat and boots do not come off because they are glued to him. Strangely enough, this character started off with the name Pippy but was renamed by the writers soon after.\n* Nedley the Rabbit: Nedley speaks in rhymes. He says rhymes almost all through every episode that he appears in, but sometimes he talks normally a little bit before starting his rhyme again. Nedley lives in a rabbit hole next to his carrot patch in Nowhere Land.\n* The Moo Sisters: They are the three cows who live in a part of Nowhere Land called Mooville. They love to sing and do it often. They are sisters and their names are Millicent, Mavis and Marge.\n* Mr. Moon: He is the only non-human and non-animal character in the episode \"Blue Moon\". He is usually grumpy because people say he is made of green cheese.\n* The Kindly Giant: The Kindly Giant is not at all scary but instead kind hearted. The others are scared at first but they soon get used to him and they sometimes go to him for advice or a favour. He refers to Maggie, Hamilton and the Beast as little ones. He owns a garden full of fruits and vegetables, from which he always lets the ever hungry Beast scarf up a giant blueberry or two. His face is never shown, and he only appears in a few episodes. He is big and strong. Even the Beast seems small compared to the giant. The Kindly Giant lives in an area of Nowhere Land where all the fruits and vegetables are giant sized. Usually, only his shoes and ankles are seen due to his largeness.\n* The Dream Sheep: White sheep that make \"baa\" sounds. They are occasionally up in the clouds.\n* The Jellybean Team: They are a group of seven jellybeans. There is a red one, an orange one, a yellow one, a purple one, a black one and two green ones. They are small, of course, but have big personalities. They also tend to argue with each other a lot because they each think they are more important than the others.\n* The Triplets: Maggie's baby cousins (Zack, Max, and Oscar). They only appear in four episodes, \"One, Two, Three\", \"Home of the Kindly Giant\", \"The New Rubber Ball\" and \"Which Way Did They Go?\".\n* Big Duck: A large duck with white feathers who lives in the water. She is the focus of the episode \"The Big Duck\" and appears in the series' theme song.\n* Reggie Van Beast: Beast's cousin. His coloring is the inverse of Beast's, being red with yellow spots, and he wears a monocle. He is rather stuck up and rude, and never really seems to enjoy anything that Beast and his friends want to do. He also often speaks in rhymes, similar to Nedley. He first appeared in \"Guess Who's Coming to Visit\".\n\n==Production==\nThe theme song for the show is \"Maggie and the Ferocious Beast in Nowhere Land,\" which is an original song by [[Isabella Molley]]. ''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast'' is produced by [[Nelvana]], and directed by [[Jamie Whitney]] and [[Stuart Shankly]]. The series debuted in 2001 and the series aired its last episode in 2003. The show is distributed by Nelvana. \n\nIn the United Kingdom, the show was dubbed with British voice actors, replacing the original Canadian soundtrack. The shorts were shown with the original voices.\n\n==Broadcast==\nIn Canada, ''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast'' aired on [[Teletoon]] and [[Treehouse TV]]. In the United States, it aired on [[Nickelodeon]] as part of its [[Nick Jr. (TV programming block)|Nick Jr.]] block from June 5, 2000, to September 6, 2004, and the American children's channel [[Nick Jr.|Noggin]] (now [[Nick Jr.]]) from April 7, 2003, until September 27, 2009, when Noggin was re-branded as Nick Jr., and continued to air reruns until October 30, 2010. The show aired in reruns on \"[[Nickelodeon on CBS|Nick on CBS]]\" from September 16, 2000, to June 9, 2001. As of May 28, 2018, it is airing on [[Qubo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qubo.com/show/maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast|title=Maggie and the Ferocious Beast {{!}} Qubo - Qubo is the nation\u2019s only 24/7 over-the-air network for children.|website=Qubo|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0262168|title= Maggie and the Ferocious Beast}}\n* {{tv.com show|maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast|Maggie and the Ferocious Beast}}\n\n{{Teletoon}}\n{{Children's programming on CBS in the 2000s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maggie And The Ferocious Beast}}\n[[Category:2000 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about pigs]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about mice and rats]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about ducks]]\n[[Category:Television series about cows]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Nick Jr. original programming]]\n[[Category:qubo]]\n[[Category:Teletoon original series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Short description|Canadian animated children's television series created by Michael and Betty Paraskevas}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Maggie and the Ferocious Beast\n| image                    = Maggie and the Ferocious Beast Logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Fantasy film|Fantasy]]\n| creator                  = [[Michael Paraskevas]] and [[Betty Paraskevas]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = Gabe Mannes\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Kristen Bone\n* [[Stephen Ouimette]]\n* Michael Caruana\n* [[Julie Lemieux]]\n* [[Adrian Truss]]\n* Tamara Bernier\n* John McGrath\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = TTG Music Lab\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Branton\n* Tony Crea\n* Mike Northcott\n}}\n| country                  = Canada\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 3\n| num_episodes             = 39 (117 segments)\n| list_episodes            = List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist |\n* Michael Hirsh\n* Patrick Loubert\n* Clive A. Smith\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Cynthia Taylor\n* Steve Hodgins\n* Patricia R. Burns (supervising)\n}}\n| editor                   = Stephanie Duncan\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[Nelvana]]\n| distributor              = Nelvana\n| channel                  = [[Teletoon]]\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2000|8|26}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2002|06|09}}\n| website                  = http://www.ferociousbeast.com/\n| production_website       = http://www.nelvana.com/show/119/maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast\n}}\n'''''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast''''' is a Canadian [[Animated series|animated]] [[children's television series]] created by [[Michael Paraskevas|Michael]] and [[Betty Paraskevas]]. The program was based on the 1996 book ''The Ferocious Beast with the Polka-Dot Hide'' and its sequels, all of which were also written by the Paraskevases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parents-choice.org/article.cfm?art_id=330&the_page=editorials|title=Inside Maggie and the Ferocious Beast|work=Parents-Choice.org|publisher=[[Parents' Choice Award|Parents' Choice Foundation]]|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe show began as a series of shorts aired on the Canadian channel [[Teletoon]] in 1998. The first full-length episode premiered on August 26, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Nelvana's+%22Maggie+and+the+Ferocious+Beast%22+soars+to+a+ferocious+No.+1...-a063944653 |title=Nelvana's \"Maggie and the Ferocious Beast\" soars to a ferocious No. 1 on Nick Jr. - Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date= |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref>   \n\nThe series began airing on [[Qubo]] on May 28, 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nA young girl named Maggie creates her own map of an imaginary world known as \"Nowhere Land\" that, in reality, takes the characters nowhere. She imagines that characters Beast and Hamilton Hocks are her friends.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes}}\n{{:List of Maggie and the Ferocious Beast episodes}}\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Main===\n* Maggie (voiced by Kristen Bone) is a five-year-old girl (who later turns six years old)  and the human protagonist of the show. She is Hamilton's and Beast's best friend. They both look up to Maggie very much and always turn to her for advice. Maggie is the leader of the group and is always there to be the compassionate voice of reason to her dear friends.\n* The Ferocious Beast (voiced by [[Stephen Ouimette]]) he is very scary or ferocious. However, he can shout louder than anybody. He is a yellow beast, with big red removable spots, and three horns on his head. His favorite catchphrase is \"Great googly moogly!\", which he says several times per episode. In \"Hide And Go Beast\", it is shown that he is allergic to pollen. He is just a big softie, despite his bold appearance. Beast loves pumpkins, which is convenient since there is an impressive pumpkin patch in Nowhere Land. As a matter of fact, Beast loves pretty much any kind of food, including Hamilton's cooking, and is almost always hungry. He even loves baths. Maggie and Hamilton are his best friends. He wears multi-colored galoshes which he pronounces as \"Goo-lashes\". Hamilton always corrects him about the pronunciation, but he does not believe him.\n* Hamilton Hocks (voiced by Michael Caruana) is a pig who can be bossy and quite fussy, but he has a warm heart. He lives inside a portable cardboard box which he loves, is the best cook in Nowhere Land, and is a total clean freak. Hamilton's most prized possessions are his beautiful \"H\" sweater and his cardboard box, which also happens to be his home. Maggie and the Beast are his best friends.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Rudy the Mouse: Rudy is a cheese-loving mouse who lives in a large wheel of cheese in a part of Nowhere Land called Cheese Town. It is revealed in one episode that Rudy's hat and boots do not come off because they are glued to him. Strangely enough, this character started off with the name Pippy but was renamed by the writers soon after.\n* Nedley the Rabbit: Nedley speaks in rhymes. He says rhymes almost all through every episode that he appears in, but sometimes he talks normally a little bit before starting his rhyme again. Nedley lives in a rabbit hole next to his carrot patch in Nowhere Land.\n* The Moo Sisters: They are the three cows who live in a part of Nowhere Land called Mooville. They love to sing and do it often. They are sisters and their names are Millicent, Mavis and Marge.\n* Mr. Moon: He is the only non-human and non-animal character in the episode \"Blue Moon\". He is usually grumpy because people say he is made of green cheese.\n* The Kindly Giant: The Kindly Giant is not at all scary but instead kind hearted. The others are scared at first but they soon get used to him and they sometimes go to him for advice or a favour. He refers to Maggie, Hamilton and the Beast as little ones. He owns a garden full of fruits and vegetables, from which he always lets the ever hungry Beast scarf up a giant blueberry or two. His face is never shown, and he only appears in a few episodes. He is big and strong. Even the Beast seems small compared to the giant. The Kindly Giant lives in an area of Nowhere Land where all the fruits and vegetables are giant sized. Usually, only his shoes and ankles are seen due to his largeness.\n* The Dream Sheep: White sheep that make \"baa\" sounds. They are occasionally up in the clouds.\n* The Jellybean Team: They are a group of seven jellybeans. There is a red one, an orange one, a yellow one, a purple one, a black one and two green ones. They are small, of course, but have big personalities. They also tend to argue with each other a lot because they each think they are more important than the others.\n* The Triplets: Maggie's baby cousins (Zack, Max, and Oscar). They only appear in four episodes, \"One, Two, Three\", \"Home of the Kindly Giant\", \"The New Rubber Ball\" and \"Which Way Did They Go?\".\n* Big Duck: A large duck with white feathers who lives in the water. She is the focus of the episode \"The Big Duck\" and appears in the series' theme song.\n* Reggie Van Beast: Beast's cousin. His coloring is the inverse of Beast's, being red with yellow spots, and he wears a monocle. He is rather stuck up and rude, and never really seems to enjoy anything that Beast and his friends want to do. He also often speaks in rhymes, similar to Nedley. He first appeared in \"Guess Who's Coming to Visit\".\n\n==Production==\nThe theme song for the show is \"Maggie and the Ferocious Beast in Nowhere Land,\" which is an original song by [[Isabella Molley]]. ''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast'' is produced by [[Nelvana]], and directed by [[Jamie Whitney]] and [[Stuart Shankly]]. The series debuted in 2000 and the series aired its last episode in 2002. The show is distributed by Nelvana. \n\nIn the United Kingdom, the show was dubbed with British voice actors, replacing the original Canadian soundtrack. The shorts were shown with the original voices.\n\n==Broadcast==\nIn Canada, ''Maggie and the Ferocious Beast'' aired on [[Teletoon]] and [[Treehouse TV]]. In the United States, it aired on [[Nickelodeon]] as part of its [[Nick Jr. (TV programming block)|Nick Jr.]] block from June 5, 2000, to September 6, 2004, and the American children's channel [[Nick Jr.|Noggin]] (now [[Nick Jr.]]) from April 7, 2003, until September 27, 2009, when Noggin was re-branded as Nick Jr., and continued to air reruns until October 30, 2010. The show aired in reruns on \"[[Nickelodeon on CBS|Nick on CBS]]\" from September 16, 2000, to June 9, 2001. As of May 28, 2018, it is airing on [[Qubo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qubo.com/show/maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast|title=Maggie and the Ferocious Beast {{!}} Qubo - Qubo is the nation\u2019s only 24/7 over-the-air network for children.|website=Qubo|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0262168|title= Maggie and the Ferocious Beast}}\n* {{tv.com show|maggie-and-the-ferocious-beast|Maggie and the Ferocious Beast}}\n\n{{Teletoon}}\n{{Children's programming on CBS in the 2000s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maggie And The Ferocious Beast}}\n[[Category:2000 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about pigs]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about mice and rats]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about ducks]]\n[[Category:Television series about cows]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Nick Jr. original programming]]\n[[Category:qubo]]\n[[Category:Teletoon original series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e34:ef60:a6b0:6c39:6708:7e92:8002", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(MAGGIE AND THE FEROCIOUS BEAST)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maggie_and_the_Ferocious_Beast"}
{"title_page": "Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image = KlipsanBeachLSS.jpg\n  | caption = A photograph of the station in 2017\n  | location= [[Klipsan Beach, Washington]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|46|27|52.89|N|124|3|8.77|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Washington\n  | area =\n  | built =1891\n| architect= Arthur B. Bibb\n| architecture= Marquette-type life-saving station\n | added = July 05, 1979\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=79002546\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Klipsan Beach''' was the site of a station of the [[United States Life-Saving Service]].  The station buildings still remain, although they are privately owned.  The station is on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].  The station's name was originally [[Ilwaco, Washington|Ilwaco]] Beach, and only later became known as Klipsan Station. The station was one of several assigned to provide protection in the area known as the [[Graveyard of the Pacific]].\n\n==Location==\nOn the [[Long Beach Peninsula]], in [[Pacific County, Washington]], about 13 miles (21&nbsp;km) north of [[Cape Disappointment (Washington)|Cape Disappointment]].\n\n==Construction and architecture==\nThe station was established in 1891.  It was built according to the \"Marquette\" style of life-saving stations, one of a number of standard station designs adopted by the [[United States Life-Saving Service]].<ref>Shanks, York, and Shanks, ''The U.S. Life-Saving Service - Heroes, Rescues and Architecture of the Early Coast Guar''d, at page 202, Costano Books, Petaluma, CA (1996) {{ISBN|0-930268-16-4}}</ref>  This pattern received its name from the station where it was first used, [[Marquette, Michigan]]. There were 13 other life-saving Marquette stations, their architect was [[Albert B. Bibb]], and it is speculated that the plans were drawn up in 1889.  Other Marquette stations on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] include those at [[Yaquina Bay]], the [[Umpqua River]], [[Coos Bay]], and the [[Coquille River (Oregon)|Coquille River]] in [[Oregon]] and at [[Southside, California]].<ref name=SYS>Shanks, York, and Shanks, at 110</ref>  \nThe boat house was also built according to a standard [[United States Life-Saving Service]] plan, called the \"witch's hat\" for the design's use of a distinct octagonal ventilator with a conical roof.\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cgi-bin/viewer.exe?CISOROOT=/wastate&CISOPTR=417&CISORESTMP=&CISOVIEWTMP= Ilwaco (later Klipsan Beach) Life Saving Station, circa 1895]\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:US Life Saving Service.gif|thumb|right|200px|Emblem of the U.S. Life-Saving Service]]\n\n===Volunteer operations===\nThe station was first started in 1889 on a volunteer basis, and called the Ilwaco Beach station.  On November 3, 1891, the ship ''Strathblane'' went aground near the station.  The volunteer crew was unable to get their lines out to the ship, and seven people died.  As a result of this, a decision was made to put the station on a full-time professional basis.<ref>Hobbs, Nancy L., and Lucero, Donella J., ''The Long Beach Peninsula'', at page 77, Arcadia Publishing 2005 {{ISBN|0-7385-2995-8}} (reprinting wreck site map)</ref>\n\n===Professional keepers===\nRichard Turk was appointed keeper on December 18, 1891 and died on December 2, 1894.  William S. Lawrence was appointed keeper on January 4, 1895 and \"services dispensed with\" on October 9, 1897.  George Jorgensen was appointed keeper on November 17, 1897 and transferred to Point Reyes on February 7, 1902. Theodore Conick was appointed keeper on that date and was still serving in 1915.  Chief Warrant Officer Joseph Henderson was listed as the Chief Officer in 1929.<ref>[http://www.uscg.mil/history/STATIONS/ILWACO%20BEACH.html U.S. Coast Guard Historian's Office -- Search and Rescue -- Historic Small Boat Stations]</ref>\n\n===Equipment===\nThe station was equipped with a Dobbins type lifeboat and a McClelland surfboat, which were launched into the surf from a four-wheel hand or horse-drawn carriage.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, Larry, \"The Life Savers of Klipsan\", T''he Sou'Wester'', Vol. 36, page 7, Pacific County Historical Society 2001] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref>  The station was also equipped with a variety of rescue equipment, including the Lyle gun, the breeches buoy, and [[Coston flare]]s.  At times, surfmen rode horses to patrol the beaches<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, \"Life Savers of Klipsan\", at 7] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref>  The station could call upon the assistance of a seaside railroad, the [[Ilwaco Railway and Navigation Company]], to move rescue boats up and down the beach to get closer to a wreck before launching.\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/transportation&CISOPTR=186&REC=2 Wreck of the ''Alice'', with Klipsan Beach life-saving crew launching boat in surf]\n\n===Use of railroad===\nThe [[Ilwaco Railway and Navigation Company]] railroad also took the crew of the station to wherever a vessel might have stranded on the beach along the line.  Occasional special runs were made to bring on-lookers to a wreck site, and weekly excursions were made to take vacationers to watch the lifeboat rescue drills at the Klipsan Beach Station.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, Larry, \"The Lifesavers of Klipsan,\" The Sou'wester, Vol. 37, No. 3, page 9, Pacific County Historical Society, South Bend, WA (Fall, 2001)] {{ISSN|0038-4984}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref><ref>Feagans, at 41</ref>  L.A. Loomis was closely involved with the establishment of the life-saving station near to the railway line, which ran along the eastern boundary of the proposed station property.  Loomis promised a siding along the northern boundary to the boathouse overlooking the ocean.  A flatcar was placed there to allow transport of rescue crews and boats to points along the beach.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, page 5] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe railroad was used in at least one rescue, on December 19, 1896, when the German bark ''Potrimpos'' drifted ashore seven miles south of the life-saving station.  The horse-drawn lifeboat was not able to get down the beach, but the railroad transported a life boat and crew to the scene of the wreck, where fourteen men were still aboard.  The lifeboat was launched, and all the men were saved.  A special train also brought up the life-saving crew from the next south station, Cape Disappointment, but by the time they arrive, all the men had been taken off the stricken bark.<ref>Newell, Gordon R., ed., ''H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest'', at page 7, Superior Publishing Co., Seattle, WA 1966</ref>\n\nThe tracks were so close to the life-saving station that surfmen and their children could and did pose for photographs on the crude platform at the station, with the rails in foreground and the station clearly shown in the background.<ref>Shanks, York, and Shanks, ''The U.S. Life-Saving Service\u2014Heroes, Rescues and Architecture of the Early Coast Guard'', at page 37, Costano Books, Petaluma, CA (1996) {{ISBN|0-930268-16-4}}</ref>\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/transportation&CISOPTR=186&REC=2 Wreck of the ''Alice'', with Klipsan Beach life-saving crew launching boat in surf]\n*[http://content.lib.washington.edu/cgi-bin/viewer.exe?CISOROOT=/wastate&CISOPTR=417&CISORESTMP=&CISOVIEWTMP= Ilwaco (later Klipsan Beach) Life Saving Station, circa 1895]\n*[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3_08a.jpg wreck of the ''Potrimpos'']\n\n===Wrecks along the North Beach===\nA partial listing of wrecks along the North Beach (that is, the ocean side of the [[Long Beach Peninsula]]) during the station's operation includes, running from north to south on the beach:<ref>Hobbs and Lucero, ''The Long Beach Peninsula'', at 70 (reprinting wreck site map)</ref>\n\n* [[schooner]] ''Solano'', February 5, 1907\n* ''Glenmorag'', March 19, 1896\n* ''Caoba'', February 5, 1925\n* [[barque|bark]] ''Alfa'', September 19, 1924\n* ''Alice'', January 15, 1909\n* ''Lenore'', April 10, 1917\n* ''Strathblane'', November 3, 1891\n* ''Artemsia'', 1889\n* ''C.A. Klose'' (or ''Close''), March 26, 1905\n* [[barque|bark]] ''Potrimpos'', December 19, 1896\n* steamer ''Point Loma'', February 28, 1896\n* [[schooner]] ''Frank W. Howe'', February 22, 1904\n\n==The station now==\nThe station is no longer on the beach, which has receded a long way since active operations ceased.  A photo from the beach when the station was active shows the beach extending to the station's watchtower and boat house.<ref>Feagans, Raymond J., ''The Railroad that Ran by the Tide -- Ilwaco Railroad and Navigation Co. of the State of Washington'', page 42, Howell-North Books, Berkeley, CA (1972) {{ISBN|0-8310-7094-3}}</ref>  This is no longer the case.  The station itself, as well as the boathouse and watchtower, remained as of 2000, and were in private ownership.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station}}\n* [http://www.learnatthebeach.com/ The Official Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station Website]\n* [http://www.uscg.mil/history/collect.html U.S. Coast Guard Historian's Office]\n* ''The Sou'Wester'', Journal of the Pacific County Historical Society, Volume 36, No. 3 (Fall, 2001), covering details of Klipsan Beach station and other life-saving stations, including equipment, history, and drills\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Washington}}\n{{Ilwaco Navigation Company}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pacific County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Life-Saving Service stations]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Pacific County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Life-Saving Service stations on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image = KlipsanBeachLSS.jpg\n  | caption = A photograph of the station in 2017\n  | location= [[Klipsan Beach, Washington]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|46|27|52.89|N|124|3|8.77|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Washington\n  | area =\n  | built =1891\n| architect= Arthur B. Bibb\n| architecture= Marquette-type life-saving station\n | added = July 05, 1979\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=79002546\n<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Klipsan Beach''' was the site of a station of the [[United States Life-Saving Service]].  The station buildings still remain, although they are privately owned.  The station is on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].  The station's name was originally [[Ilwaco, Washington|Ilwaco]] Beach, and only later became known as Klipsan Station. The station was one of several assigned to protect the area known as the [[Graveyard of the Pacific]].\n\n==Location==\nOn the [[Long Beach Peninsula]], in [[Pacific County, Washington]], about 13 miles (21&nbsp;km) north of [[Cape Disappointment (Washington)|Cape Disappointment]].\n\n==Construction and architecture==\nThe station was established in 1891.  It was built according to the \"Marquette\" style of life-saving stations, one of a number of standard station designs adopted by the [[United States Life-Saving Service]].<ref>Shanks, York, and Shanks, ''The U.S. Life-Saving Service - Heroes, Rescues and Architecture of the Early Coast Guar''d, at page 202, Costano Books, Petaluma, CA (1996) {{ISBN|0-930268-16-4}}</ref>  This pattern received its name from the station where it was first used, [[Marquette, Michigan]]. There were 13 other life-saving Marquette stations, their architect was [[Albert B. Bibb]], and it is speculated that the plans were drawn up in 1889.  Other Marquette stations on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] include those at [[Yaquina Bay]], the [[Umpqua River]], [[Coos Bay]], and the [[Coquille River (Oregon)|Coquille River]] in [[Oregon]] and at [[Southside, California]].<ref name=SYS>Shanks, York, and Shanks, at 110</ref>  \nThe boat house was also built according to a standard [[United States Life-Saving Service]] plan, called the \"witch's hat\" for the design's use of a distinct octagonal ventilator with a conical roof.\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cgi-bin/viewer.exe?CISOROOT=/wastate&CISOPTR=417&CISORESTMP=&CISOVIEWTMP= Ilwaco (later Klipsan Beach) Life Saving Station, circa 1895]\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:US Life Saving Service.gif|thumb|right|200px|Emblem of the U.S. Life-Saving Service]]\n\n===Volunteer operations===\nThe station was first started in 1889 on a volunteer basis, and called the Ilwaco Beach station.  On November 3, 1891, the ship ''Strathblane'' went aground near the station.  The volunteer crew was unable to get their lines out to the ship, and seven people died.  As a result of this, a decision was made to put the station on a full-time professional basis.<ref>Hobbs, Nancy L., and Lucero, Donella J., ''The Long Beach Peninsula'', at page 77, Arcadia Publishing 2005 {{ISBN|0-7385-2995-8}} (reprinting wreck site map)</ref>\n\n===Professional keepers===\nRichard Turk was appointed keeper on December 18, 1891 and died on December 2, 1894.  William S. Lawrence was appointed keeper on January 4, 1895 and \"services dispensed with\" on October 9, 1897.  George Jorgensen was appointed keeper on November 17, 1897 and transferred to Point Reyes on February 7, 1902. Theodore Conick was appointed keeper on that date and was still serving in 1915.  Chief Warrant Officer Joseph Henderson was listed as the Chief Officer in 1929.<ref>[http://www.uscg.mil/history/STATIONS/ILWACO%20BEACH.html U.S. Coast Guard Historian's Office -- Search and Rescue -- Historic Small Boat Stations]</ref>\n\n===Equipment===\nThe station was equipped with a Dobbins type lifeboat and a McClelland surfboat, which were launched into the surf from a four-wheel hand or horse-drawn carriage.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, Larry, \"The Life Savers of Klipsan\", T''he Sou'Wester'', Vol. 36, page 7, Pacific County Historical Society 2001] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref>  The station was also equipped with a variety of rescue equipment, including the Lyle gun, the breeches buoy, and [[Coston flare]]s.  At times, surfmen rode horses to patrol the beaches<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, \"Life Savers of Klipsan\", at 7] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref>  The station could call upon the assistance of a seaside railroad, the [[Ilwaco Railway and Navigation Company]], to move rescue boats up and down the beach to get closer to a wreck before launching.\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/transportation&CISOPTR=186&REC=2 Wreck of the ''Alice'', with Klipsan Beach life-saving crew launching boat in surf]\n\n===Use of railroad===\nThe [[Ilwaco Railway and Navigation Company]] railroad also took the crew of the station to wherever a vessel might have stranded on the beach along the line.  Occasional special runs were made to bring on-lookers to a wreck site, and weekly excursions were made to take vacationers to watch the lifeboat rescue drills at the Klipsan Beach Station.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, Larry, \"The Lifesavers of Klipsan,\" The Sou'wester, Vol. 37, No. 3, page 9, Pacific County Historical Society, South Bend, WA (Fall, 2001)] {{ISSN|0038-4984}} {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref><ref>Feagans, at 41</ref>  L.A. Loomis was closely involved with the establishment of the life-saving station near to the railway line, which ran along the eastern boundary of the proposed station property.  Loomis promised a siding along the northern boundary to the boathouse overlooking the ocean.  A flatcar was placed there to allow transport of rescue crews and boats to points along the beach.<ref>[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm Weathers, page 5] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025841/http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3.htm |date=2007-12-17 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe railroad was used in at least one rescue, on December 19, 1896, when the German bark ''Potrimpos'' drifted ashore seven miles south of the life-saving station.  The horse-drawn lifeboat was not able to get down the beach, but the railroad transported a life boat and crew to the scene of the wreck, where fourteen men were still aboard.  The lifeboat was launched, and all the men were saved.  A special train also brought up the life-saving crew from the next south station, Cape Disappointment, but by the time they arrive, all the men had been taken off the stricken bark.<ref>Newell, Gordon R., ed., ''H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest'', at page 7, Superior Publishing Co., Seattle, WA 1966</ref>\n\nThe tracks were so close to the life-saving station that surfmen and their children could and did pose for photographs on the crude platform at the station, with the rails in foreground and the station clearly shown in the background.<ref>Shanks, York, and Shanks, ''The U.S. Life-Saving Service\u2014Heroes, Rescues and Architecture of the Early Coast Guard'', at page 37, Costano Books, Petaluma, CA (1996) {{ISBN|0-930268-16-4}}</ref>\n* [http://content.lib.washington.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/transportation&CISOPTR=186&REC=2 Wreck of the ''Alice'', with Klipsan Beach life-saving crew launching boat in surf]\n*[http://content.lib.washington.edu/cgi-bin/viewer.exe?CISOROOT=/wastate&CISOPTR=417&CISORESTMP=&CISOVIEWTMP= Ilwaco (later Klipsan Beach) Life Saving Station, circa 1895]\n*[http://www.pacificcohistory.org/sw2001_3_08a.jpg wreck of the ''Potrimpos'']\n\n===Wrecks along the North Beach===\nA partial listing of wrecks along the North Beach (that is, the ocean side of the [[Long Beach Peninsula]]) during the station's operation includes, running from north to south on the beach:<ref>Hobbs and Lucero, ''The Long Beach Peninsula'', at 70 (reprinting wreck site map)</ref>\n\n* [[schooner]] ''Solano'', February 5, 1907\n* ''Glenmorag'', March 19, 1896\n* ''Caoba'', February 5, 1925\n* [[barque|bark]] ''Alfa'', September 19, 1924\n* ''Alice'', January 15, 1909\n* ''Lenore'', April 10, 1917\n* ''Strathblane'', November 3, 1891\n* ''Artemsia'', 1889\n* ''C.A. Klose'' (or ''Close''), March 26, 1905\n* [[barque|bark]] ''Potrimpos'', December 19, 1896\n* steamer ''Point Loma'', February 28, 1896\n* [[schooner]] ''Frank W. Howe'', February 22, 1904\n\n==The station now==\nThe station is no longer on the beach, which has receded a long way since active operations ceased.  A photo from the beach when the station was active shows the beach extending to the station's watchtower and boat house.<ref>Feagans, Raymond J., ''The Railroad that Ran by the Tide -- Ilwaco Railroad and Navigation Co. of the State of Washington'', page 42, Howell-North Books, Berkeley, CA (1972) {{ISBN|0-8310-7094-3}}</ref>  This is no longer the case.  The station itself, as well as the boathouse and watchtower, remained as of 2000, and were in private ownership.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station}}\n* [http://www.learnatthebeach.com/ The Official Klipsan Beach Life Saving Station Website]\n* [http://www.uscg.mil/history/collect.html U.S. Coast Guard Historian's Office]\n* ''The Sou'Wester'', Journal of the Pacific County Historical Society, Volume 36, No. 3 (Fall, 2001), covering details of Klipsan Beach station and other life-saving stations, including equipment, history, and drills\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Washington}}\n{{Ilwaco Navigation Company}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pacific County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Life-Saving Service stations]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Pacific County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Life-Saving Service stations on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n", "name_user": "Writhing", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klipsan_Beach_Life_Saving_Station"}
{"title_page": "Roman Brady", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character from Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Days of our Lives\n| image1 = File:joshasroman.jpg\n| caption1 = Josh Taylor as Roman Brady \n| image2 = File:DOOLNorthrop-Roman.jpg\n| caption2 = Wayne Northrop as Roman Brady (1983)\n| image3 = File:Drake_Hogestyn_as_Roman.jpg\n| caption3 = Drake Hogestyn as [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|\"Roman\"]] (1986)\n| name = Roman Brady\n| portrayer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Wayne Northrop]] (December 1981\u2013 December 1984, September 1991-August 1994)\n* [[Josh Taylor (actor)|Josh Taylor]] (September 1997\u2013present) \n}} \n| creator = [[Pat Falken Smith]]\n| introducer = [[Betty Corday]] and [[Al Rabin]]\n| years = {{Flat list |\n*1981\u201384\n*1991\u201394\n*1997\u2013present\n}}\n| first = {{start date|1981|12}}\n| last = \n| appeared = <!-- for an episode date if the episode is unnamed -->\n| only = <!-- for an episode title or season -->\n| classification = [[Days of Our Lives cast members#Main cast|Present; regular]]\n| books = \n| spinoffs = \n| alias = \n| occupation = Police commissioner (retired)\n| home = Salem, [[United States|Illinois]]\n| family = Brady family\n| spouse= {{ubl|[[Anna DiMera|Anna Brady]] (until 1982)|[[Marlena Evans]] (1983\u201394)|[[Kate Roberts (Days of our Lives)|Kate Roberts]] (2003\u201305)}}\n| husband= \n| parents= {{ubl|[[Shawn Brady]]|[[Caroline Brady]]}}\n| brothers = {{ubl|[[Frankie Brady]] (adoptive)|[[Max Brady]] (adoptive)}}\n| sisters = {{ubl|[[Kimberly Brady]]|[[Kayla Brady]]}}\n| halfbrothers = [[Bo Brady]]\n| sons = {{ubl|[[Eric Brady]]|[[Rex Brady]]}}\n| daughters = {{ubl|[[Carrie Brady]]|[[Sami Brady]]|[[Cassie Brady]]}}\n| grandsons = {{ubl|[[Will Horton]]|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Johnny DiMera|Johnny DiMera]]|Noah Reed}}\n| granddaughters = {{ubl|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Allie Horton|Allie Horton]]|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Sydney DiMera|Sydney DiMera]]}}Emily Lockhart <br> Mackenzie Horton \n| grandparents= Peter Brady\n| aunts/uncles= Eric Brady<br>[[Colleen Brady]] <br> Molly Murphy \n| cousins= Ryan Brady <br> [[Colin Murphy (Days of our Lives)|Colin Murphy]] \n| nieces/nephews= Andrew Donovan <br> [[Theresa Donovan]] <br> [[Stephanie Johnson (Days of Our Lives)|Stephanie Johnson]] <br> [[Joey Johnson (Days of Our Lives)|Joey Johnson]] <br> [[Shawn-Douglas Brady]] <br> [[Chelsea Brady]] <br> [[Zack Brady]] <br> [[Ciara Brady]]\n}}\n'''Roman Brady''' is a [[fictional character]] from the long-running [[NBC]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. The role was originated in December 1981 by [[Wayne Northrop]], who played the role until  December 1984, was filled by [[Drake Hogestyn]] from May 1986 to December 1991, again by [[Wayne Northrop|Northrop]] from september  1991 to August 1994, and is currently being portrayed by series veteran [[Josh Taylor (actor)|Josh Taylor]], who stepped into the role in  september 1997.\n\n==Casting==\nThe role was originated on December  1981, by Wayne Northrop.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/12/history-december-8_7.html|title = Today in Soap Opera History (December 8)|date = December 8, 2012|first = Roger|last = Newcomb|work = [[We Love Soaps]]|accessdate = December 19, 2012}}</ref> Northrop departed from the series In December 1984, and the character was killed off during a battle with his arch-nemesis, international criminal mastermind [[Stefano DiMera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/11/history-november-26.html|title=Today in Soap Opera History (November 26)|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|date=November 26, 2012|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> In November 1985, the series introduced a character known as The Pawn.<ref>{{YouTube|id=4XS1Sb3pdGs|title=Kim & Shane/The Pawn \u2013 11/27/85 pt. 1}}</ref> The role was portrayed by Robert Poynton until January 1986, though the character's face is wrapped in bandages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/john.php|title=About DAYS: Who's Who in Salem {{!}} John Black|work=[[Soapcentral]]|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> In January 1986, The Pawn's bandages were finally removed as [[Drake Hogestyn]] made his first appearance as [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]], a character with no memory of his past or knowledge of his real identity.<ref>Lucille Giordano, ''Inside Days of Our Lives'' July 1995.</ref> In May 1986, Hogestyn's character of John is revealed to be Roman with extensive plastic surgery and Hogestyn played the role written as Roman until  December 1991. When Northrop returned as Roman in September 1991, the character that Hogestyn had been portraying for five years was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] to be an entirely separate character that had been brainwashed to believe he was Roman Brady.<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book | author = Maureen Russell | title = Days of Our Lives: A Complete History of the Long-Running Soap Opera | chapter= Bibliography |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WwI5PzDiIKcC&pg=PA266&lpg=PA266&dq=days+of+our+lives+wayne+northrop+return+August+1991&source=bl&ots=FwyaMDz51b&sig=GH97-UX8GWVOqP6nlkwNDvK2W4c&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AqPSUPbMDbS30AGS04CICA&ved=0CFwQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=days%20of%20our%20lives%20wayne%20northrop%20return%20August%201991&f=false|publisher=McFarland & Company, Incorporated Publishers|year=2010|pages=266|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> Northrop once again departed from the series in August 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/08/historyaugust2.html|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|title=Today in Soap Opera History (August 2)|date=August 2, 2012|work=We Loves Soaps|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> In September 1997, Josh Taylor appeared in the role as a recast of Roman Brady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/07/historyjuly18.html|title=Today in Soap Opera History (July 18)|date=July 18, 2012|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|work=We Loves Soaps|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> The casting was met with criticism due to Taylor's previous portrayal of [[Chris Kositchek]], one of Roman and Marlena's closest friends. Northrop was later recast as another new character, [[Alex North (fiction)|Dr. Alex North]], and scenes from Northrop's time playing Roman were edited to create the new character's backstory.\n\n==Characterization==\nRoman is the retired police commissioner of the fictional Midwestern town of Salem, and currently manages and tends bar at his family's business, the Brady Pub. He is also a former agent of the fictional [[ISA (Days of Our Lives)|International Security Alliance]] (ISA), a spy agency focused on all sorts of unusually high-level global conspiracies that tended to center around his otherwise-quiet home town. During his portrayal by Northrop, he was established as a top-notch cop but also a bit of a renegade, often accepting deep-cover assignments, and a master of disguise (similar to Sherlock Holmes). Hogestyn's character was more by-the-book on the job, although still dangerous with a dark side somewhat characteristic of an ex-spy (which later fed into the \"John Black\" persona), with expertise in [[Bruce Lee]]'s [[Jeet Kune Do]], and a little more of a ladies' man. Taylor's portrayal is more that of a \"regular guy\", with a bit less intrigue and more straightforward professionally, although still with an eye for the ladies and more inclined to engage in [[one night stand|one-night stands]] with various women than the character as portrayed by Northrop or Hogestyn (such as with Kate Roberts, Billie Reed, ex-wives Anna DiMera and Marlena Evans, and a strongly hinted at \u2013 but never confirmed \u2013 rendezvous with Nicole Walker).\n\nOver the years, much has been made of the creation (and constant [[retcon]] of the backstory) of [[Drake Hogestyn|Hogestyn's]] character John Black as an entirely separate character than that of Roman Brady, especially after the show had invested over five years in establishing John's identity as Roman, complete with a plausible backstory of his \u201ctime away\u201d (while he was being held captive, brainwashed, and trained\u2014-unsuccessfully\u2014-to be an assassin by Stefano DiMera), and \"Roman's\" reemerging memories. However, with Roman's recasts and changes in characterization over the years (while John has consistently been played by Hogestyn), in hindsight it can be said that it was actually John Black that remained more true to the original \"Roman\" persona, and that it was Roman that was gradually developed into a separate character. This was especially illustrated in 2016 when Roman, who had always been a straight-shooter with regard to the law, became complicit in the cover-up of sister-in-law [[Hope Brady]]'s murder of [[Stefano DiMera]], who she wrongly believed was responsible for the disappearance and later death of her husband (and Roman's brother) [[Bo Brady]].\n\n== Storylines ==\n\n===1981\u201384===\nRoman Brady first appeared on Days to protect Marlena Evans from a serial killer.<ref>Days of Our Lives Episode dated January 8, 1982</ref> He slept on her floor. The chemistry between the actors, and the characters, led to love. In 1983 on Days of Our Lives, Roman and Marlena were married. Over the next year Roman became embroiled in a storyline with Stefano DiMera. Stefano was a powerful and ruthless business tycoon (and organized crime figure) from Europe who had come to town to set up shop in Salem, and Roman being the city's top cop had gone after him. Subsequently Stefano framed Roman for serial killings that were being committed by his nephew Andre DiMera. At the time Marlena saw Roman killing a woman. Later it was shown that Andre had used a realistic mask. Roman was jailed. Mrs. Alice Horton baked him some drugged doughnuts, and on the way to the hospital Roman escaped. He went on the run to prove his innocence, and he accomplished that. He was promoted, and Stefano was on the run.\n\nIn November 1984 Roman tracked Stefano to a Caribbean island where many other characters had crash-landed, too. Stefano was suffering from incurable cancer, and needed to collect three mysterious prisms to unlock a secret formula to cure himself. Roman caught up to him on a cliff, but Stefano pulled a gun. He shot Roman, who seemingly fell to his death. His brother Bo cradled him in his arms on the beach, but had to leave him for a few minutes. When he returned the body was gone. Bo assumed that while he was away, the tide had come in and washed Roman\u2019s body out to sea, for which Bo blamed himself for years. Several episodes later Roman was shown aboard Stefano's yacht, motionless.\n\n===1986\u20131990===\n:{{main|John Black (Days of our Lives)}}\nIn 1986 an amnesiac known only as \"The Pawn\" appeared in Salem on January 23, 1986.<ref>Lucille Giordano, Inside Days of Our Lives July 1995.</ref> He assumed the name \"John Black\" after reading it on a Vietnam War memorial in Salem. Eventually the character was revealed to be Roman Brady having undergone extensive plastic surgery, brainwashing, and martial arts training (purportedly to be trained as an assassin) by Stefano DiMera. After an uneasy \"re-introduction\" to his family and friends in Salem, the character resumed his life as Roman.\n\nIn 1988, a storyline featuring a reappearance by Stefano (who had been believed dead) focused on what had happened to Roman during his time in captivity (1984\u20131986). Roman and loved ones traveled back to the Caribbean island where Roman had \"died\" in 1984, and it was revealed that the ISA knew all along that Roman was being held by Stefano and being trained via brainwashing, and extensive instruction by a martial arts master named Orion Hawk, to be one of Stefano's assassins. In fact, the ISA unsuccessfully tried to infiltrate Orion's training camp to extract Roman, but this failed due to the high level of security at Stefano's compound as well as Roman's brainwashed state. This tied into the introduction of [[Benjy Hawk|Benjy]], Stefano's son (and Orion's grandson) who was fostered for a while by [[Steve Johnson (Days of our Lives)|Steve]] and [[Kayla Johnson]]. Although subtle hints pointed to the possibility of this \"Roman\" turning out to be someone else, abetted by speculation by fans and by [[Drake Hogestyn|Hogestyn]] himself, the clues seemed to tie back together with the resolution that, at least for the moment, the character portrayed by Hogestyn was in fact Roman Brady.\n\n===1991\u201394===\nAfter believing that Roman's wife, Marlena Evans, had been dead for some years, he had fallen in love with a woman named [[Isabella Toscano]]. In 1991 Marlena turns up alive. In August 1991 the character who had been presumed as Roman Brady since 1986 is retroactively revealed to be a separate character (now once again called John Black) who was brainwashed to believe he was Roman, when what would now be the real Roman (once again played by Wayne Northrop) was found on an island where he had been imprisoned by Stefano. Roman was shocked when he found he had been replaced and all his family had accepted John Black as him and John Black had a difficult time accepting he was not really Roman. Roman went back to his life, and he and Marlena tried to live once again as man and wife. After the death of Isabella, in his grief John turned to Marlena for comfort. The two found themselves unable to resolve their feelings for each other from their life together when John believed himself to be Roman. He and Marlena had an affair that resulted in the birth of a daughter, [[Belle Black|Isabella]], named after [[Isabella Toscano]], whom Roman believed to be his own daughter. When he discovered that Marlena and John had an affair and that Belle was not his real daughter, Roman was crushed. In June 1994, Roman leaves town broken and bitter, once again with no family.<ref>{{cite episode|series= Days Of Our Lives |series-link= Days of Our Lives |number = 7304|network=[[NBC]]|credits= [[Ken Corday]] and [[Tom Langan]] ([[Executive producer]]s); [[James E. Reilly]] ([[Head writer]]) |season = 28|date=June 15, 1994 |accessdate= May 22, 2017}}</ref> Later it was said that Roman had died on a mission for the [[ISA (Days of our Lives)|ISA]].\n\n===Late 1990s \u2013 Early 2000s===\nIn 1997 Josh Taylor was brought in as Roman, who was revealed by Stefano DiMera and Kristen Blake to be alive after being exposed to biological warfare while on a deep-cover ISA mission in South America. The cure to his ailment was discovered by John, Hope, and Stefano in a jungle mission that was engineered to drive John and Marlena apart, but in the end had the opposite result.\n\nRoman was \"killed\" during the Salem Stalker Murders in December 2003 during his wedding reception to Kate Roberts, but again was revealed to not really be dead. He lived on the island of Melaswen (New Salem) with every other victim from the Salem Stalker Murders, including Marlena. Eventually, other Salemites arrived on the island, trying to find their \"dead\" loved ones. Some of them went out in the jungle, looking for a way off the island, while the rest remained in \"Salem\" waiting for help. Help finally arrived. Jennifer got to the island, then Hope and Patrick and finally Bo and John. Everyone banded together to get off the island, but Tony wasn't going to make it easy. He created a volcanic eruption, which eventually caused a giant wave. As everyone gathered on makeshift rafts to get off the island, the wave crashed over them. The Coast Guard arrived and managed to rescue some of them, but Roman, Marlena, Jack, and his daughter Cassie were not saved. They were in the clutches of Tony DiMera once again, and he took them to a remote European castle where he held them captive.\n\nWhile in the castle, Tony DiMera (actually Andre DiMera) tormented Roman and Marlena with video of John and Kate growing ever closer back in Salem. Eventually, they believed the two of them had sex, and Roman and Marlena, needing comfort, had sex as well. Shortly thereafter, Jack made his way into their room. They escaped! Through fire and explosions, our group of intrepid Salemites \u2013 Marlena, Roman, Jack and Cassie \u2013 all got out and were on their way home.\n\nOn the ISA jet on the way back to Salem, Roman and Marlena made the decision to not tell Kate and John that they had sex. Marlena was uncomfortable with lying to John, but eventually agreed with Roman. When they arrived back they were shocked to learn that John and Kate had fallen in love and were engaged to be married, but Roman and Marlena still didn't tell the truth about their affair. Soon after they were back Marlena discovered that she was pregnant and that Roman had to be the father, but when the truth came out John wasn't too forgiving. During a fight between Roman and John, Marlena tumbled down the stairs, causing a miscarriage.\n\n===2010s===\nAs the second decade of the 21st century has unfolded, Roman is the commissioner of the Salem police force. After an ill-fated marriage to Kate Roberts, he has remained single and adopted an elder-statesman, back-burner role on the show. He serves primarily as the de facto patriarch of the Brady family and the supervisor and occasional voice-of-reason to junior police officers and ISA agents (with a [[catchphrase]] of sorts developing from his consistent inquiries of \"what da hell\" is going on). He has largely made peace with his past with [[Stefano DiMera]], [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]], and [[Victor Kiriakis]], and remains friends with ex-wives Anna DiMera, [[Marlena Evans]], and Kate Roberts, and is occasionally shown as having a soft spot for all of them. In March 2017 he retired as police commissioner and was seen in a later episode tending bar at the Brady Pub. In 2018 he began working with his friends John Black and Steve Johnson at their private detective business, Black Patch.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/roman.php Roman at '''soap'''central.'''com''']\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of Our Lives characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brady, Roman}}\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional police captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional American police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional police commissioners]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Days of our Lives\n| image1 = File:joshasroman.jpg\n| caption1 = Josh Taylor as Roman Brady\n| image2 = File:DOOLNorthrop-Roman.jpg\n| caption2 = Wayne Northrop as Roman Brady\n| image3 = File:Drake_Hogestyn_as_Roman.jpg\n| caption3 = Drake Hogestyn as [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|\"Roman\"]]\n| name = Roman Brady\n| portrayer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Wayne Northrop]] (1981\u201384, 1991\u201394)\n* [[Josh Taylor (actor)|Josh Taylor]] (1997\u2013) \n}} \n| creator = [[Pat Falken Smith]]\n| introducer = [[Betty Corday]] and [[Al Rabin]]\n| years = {{Flat list |\n*1981\u201384\n*1991\u201394\n*1997\u2013\n}}\n| first = {{start date|1981|12|08}}\n| last = \n| appeared = <!-- for an episode date if the episode is unnamed -->\n| only = <!-- for an episode title or season -->\n| classification = [[Days of Our Lives cast members#Main cast|Present; regular]]\n| books = \n| spinoffs = \n| alias = \n| occupation = Police commissioner (retired)\n| home = Salem, [[United States|Illinois]]\n| family = Brady family\n| spouse= {{ubl|[[Anna DiMera|Anna Brady]] (until 1982)|[[Marlena Evans]] (1983\u201394)|[[Kate Roberts (Days of our Lives)|Kate Roberts]] (2003\u201305)}}\n| husband= \n| parents= {{ubl|[[Shawn Brady]]|[[Caroline Brady]]}}\n| brothers = {{ubl|[[Frankie Brady]] (adoptive)|[[Max Brady]] (adoptive)}}\n| sisters = {{ubl|[[Kimberly Brady]]|[[Kayla Brady]]}}\n| halfbrothers = [[Bo Brady]]\n| sons = {{ubl|[[Eric Brady]]|[[Rex Brady]]}}\n| daughters = {{ubl|[[Carrie Brady]]|[[Sami Brady]]|[[Cassie Brady]]}}\n| grandsons = {{ubl|[[Will Horton]]|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Johnny DiMera|Johnny DiMera]]|Noah Reed}}\n| granddaughters = {{ubl|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Allie Horton|Allie Horton]]|[[Days of Our Lives characters (2000s)#Sydney DiMera|Sydney DiMera]]}}Emily Lockhart <br> Mackenzie Horton \n| grandparents= Peter Brady\n| aunts/uncles= Eric Brady<br>[[Colleen Brady]] <br> Molly Murphy \n| cousins= Ryan Brady <br> [[Colin Murphy (Days of our Lives)|Colin Murphy]] \n| nieces/nephews= Andrew Donovan <br> [[Theresa Donovan]] <br> [[Stephanie Johnson (Days of Our Lives)|Stephanie Johnson]] <br> [[Joey Johnson (Days of Our Lives)|Joey Johnson]] <br> [[Shawn-Douglas Brady]] <br> [[Chelsea Brady]] <br> [[Zack Brady]] <br> [[Ciara Brady]]\n}}\n'''Roman Brady''' is a [[fictional character]] from the long-running [[NBC]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. The role was originated in 1981 by [[Wayne Northrop]], who played the role until 1984, was filled by [[Drake Hogestyn]] from 1986 to 1991, again by [[Wayne Northrop|Northrop]] from 1991 to 1994, and is currently being portrayed by series veteran [[Josh Taylor (actor)|Josh Taylor]], who stepped into the role in 1997.\n\n==Casting==\nThe role was originated on December 8, 1981, by Wayne Northrop.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/12/history-december-8_7.html|title = Today in Soap Opera History (December 8)|date = December 8, 2012|first = Roger|last = Newcomb|work = [[We Love Soaps]]|accessdate = December 19, 2012}}</ref> Northrop departed from the series on November 26, 1984, and the character was killed off during a battle with his arch-nemesis, international criminal mastermind [[Stefano DiMera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/11/history-november-26.html|title=Today in Soap Opera History (November 26)|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|date=November 26, 2012|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> On November 27, 1985, the series introduced a character known as The Pawn.<ref>{{YouTube|id=4XS1Sb3pdGs|title=Kim & Shane/The Pawn \u2013 11/27/85 pt. 1}}</ref> The role was portrayed by Robert Poynton until January 20, 1986, though the character's face is wrapped in bandages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/john.php|title=About DAYS: Who's Who in Salem {{!}} John Black|work=[[Soapcentral]]|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> On January 23, 1986, The Pawn's bandages were finally removed as [[Drake Hogestyn]] made his first appearance as [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]], a character with no memory of his past or knowledge of his real identity.<ref>Lucille Giordano, ''Inside Days of Our Lives'' July 1995.</ref> In May 1986, Hogestyn's character of John is revealed to be Roman with extensive plastic surgery and Hogestyn played the role written as Roman until 1991. When Northrop returned as Roman on August 30, 1991, the character that Hogestyn had been portraying for five years was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] to be an entirely separate character that had been brainwashed to believe he was Roman Brady.<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book | author = Maureen Russell | title = Days of Our Lives: A Complete History of the Long-Running Soap Opera | chapter= Bibliography |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WwI5PzDiIKcC&pg=PA266&lpg=PA266&dq=days+of+our+lives+wayne+northrop+return+August+1991&source=bl&ots=FwyaMDz51b&sig=GH97-UX8GWVOqP6nlkwNDvK2W4c&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AqPSUPbMDbS30AGS04CICA&ved=0CFwQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=days%20of%20our%20lives%20wayne%20northrop%20return%20August%201991&f=false|publisher=McFarland & Company, Incorporated Publishers|year=2010|pages=266|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> Northrop once again departed from the series on August 2, 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/08/historyaugust2.html|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|title=Today in Soap Opera History (August 2)|date=August 2, 2012|work=We Loves Soaps|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> On July 18, 1997, Josh Taylor appeared in the role as a recast of Roman Brady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welovesoaps.net/2012/07/historyjuly18.html|title=Today in Soap Opera History (July 18)|date=July 18, 2012|first=Roger|last=Newcomb|work=We Loves Soaps|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref> The casting was met with criticism due to Taylor's previous portrayal of [[Chris Kositchek]], one of Roman and Marlena's closest friends. Northrop was later recast as another new character, [[Alex North (fiction)|Dr. Alex North]], and scenes from Northrop's time playing Roman were edited to create the new character's backstory.\n\n==Characterization==\nRoman is the retired police commissioner of the fictional Midwestern town of Salem, and currently manages and tends bar at his family's business, the Brady Pub. He is also a former agent of the fictional [[ISA (Days of Our Lives)|International Security Alliance]] (ISA), a spy agency focused on all sorts of unusually high-level global conspiracies that tended to center around his otherwise-quiet home town. During his portrayal by Northrop, he was established as a top-notch cop but also a bit of a renegade, often accepting deep-cover assignments, and a master of disguise (similar to Sherlock Holmes). Hogestyn's character was more by-the-book on the job, although still dangerous with a dark side somewhat characteristic of an ex-spy (which later fed into the \"John Black\" persona), with expertise in [[Bruce Lee]]'s [[Jeet Kune Do]], and a little more of a ladies' man. Taylor's portrayal is more that of a \"regular guy\", with a bit less intrigue and more straightforward professionally, although still with an eye for the ladies and more inclined to engage in [[one night stand|one-night stands]] with various women than the character as portrayed by Northrop or Hogestyn (such as with Kate Roberts, Billie Reed, ex-wives Anna DiMera and Marlena Evans, and a strongly hinted at \u2013 but never confirmed \u2013 rendezvous with Nicole Walker).\n\nOver the years, much has been made of the creation (and constant [[retcon]] of the backstory) of [[Drake Hogestyn|Hogestyn's]] character John Black as an entirely separate character than that of Roman Brady, especially after the show had invested over five years in establishing John's identity as Roman, complete with a plausible backstory of his \u201ctime away\u201d (while he was being held captive, brainwashed, and trained\u2014-unsuccessfully\u2014-to be an assassin by Stefano DiMera), and \"Roman's\" reemerging memories. However, with Roman's recasts and changes in characterization over the years (while John has consistently been played by Hogestyn), in hindsight it can be said that it was actually John Black that remained more true to the original \"Roman\" persona, and that it was Roman that was gradually developed into a separate character. This was especially illustrated in 2016 when Roman, who had always been a straight-shooter with regard to the law, became complicit in the cover-up of sister-in-law [[Hope Brady]]'s murder of [[Stefano DiMera]], who she wrongly believed was responsible for the disappearance and later death of her husband (and Roman's brother) [[Bo Brady]].\n\n== Storylines ==\n\n===1981\u201384===\nRoman Brady first appeared on Days to protect Marlena Evans from a serial killer.<ref>Days of Our Lives Episode dated January 8, 1982</ref> He slept on her floor. The chemistry between the actors, and the characters, led to love. In 1983 on Days of Our Lives, Roman and Marlena were married. Over the next year Roman became embroiled in a storyline with Stefano DiMera. Stefano was a powerful and ruthless business tycoon (and organized crime figure) from Europe who had come to town to set up shop in Salem, and Roman being the city's top cop had gone after him. Subsequently Stefano framed Roman for serial killings that were being committed by his nephew Andre DiMera. At the time Marlena saw Roman killing a woman. Later it was shown that Andre had used a realistic mask. Roman was jailed. Mrs. Alice Horton baked him some drugged doughnuts, and on the way to the hospital Roman escaped. He went on the run to prove his innocence, and he accomplished that. He was promoted, and Stefano was on the run.\n\nIn November 1984 Roman tracked Stefano to a Caribbean island where many other characters had crash-landed, too. Stefano was suffering from incurable cancer, and needed to collect three mysterious prisms to unlock a secret formula to cure himself. Roman caught up to him on a cliff, but Stefano pulled a gun. He shot Roman, who seemingly fell to his death. His brother Bo cradled him in his arms on the beach, but had to leave him for a few minutes. When he returned the body was gone. Bo assumed that while he was away, the tide had come in and washed Roman\u2019s body out to sea, for which Bo blamed himself for years. Several episodes later Roman was shown aboard Stefano's yacht, motionless.\n\n===1986\u20131990===\n:{{main|John Black (Days of our Lives)}}\nIn 1986 an amnesiac known only as \"The Pawn\" appeared in Salem on January 23, 1986.<ref>Lucille Giordano, Inside Days of Our Lives July 1995.</ref> He assumed the name \"John Black\" after reading it on a Vietnam War memorial in Salem. Eventually the character was revealed to be Roman Brady having undergone extensive plastic surgery, brainwashing, and martial arts training (purportedly to be trained as an assassin) by Stefano DiMera. After an uneasy \"re-introduction\" to his family and friends in Salem, the character resumed his life as Roman.\n\nIn 1988, a storyline featuring a reappearance by Stefano (who had been believed dead) focused on what had happened to Roman during his time in captivity (1984\u20131986). Roman and loved ones traveled back to the Caribbean island where Roman had \"died\" in 1984, and it was revealed that the ISA knew all along that Roman was being held by Stefano and being trained via brainwashing, and extensive instruction by a martial arts master named Orion Hawk, to be one of Stefano's assassins. In fact, the ISA unsuccessfully tried to infiltrate Orion's training camp to extract Roman, but this failed due to the high level of security at Stefano's compound as well as Roman's brainwashed state. This tied into the introduction of [[Benjy Hawk|Benjy]], Stefano's son (and Orion's grandson) who was fostered for a while by [[Steve Johnson (Days of our Lives)|Steve]] and [[Kayla Johnson]]. Although subtle hints pointed to the possibility of this \"Roman\" turning out to be someone else, abetted by speculation by fans and by [[Drake Hogestyn|Hogestyn]] himself, the clues seemed to tie back together with the resolution that, at least for the moment, the character portrayed by Hogestyn was in fact Roman Brady.\n\n===1991\u201394===\nAfter believing that Roman's wife, Marlena Evans, had been dead for some years, he had fallen in love with a woman named [[Isabella Toscano]]. In 1991 Marlena turns up alive. In August 1991 the character who had been presumed as Roman Brady since 1986 is retroactively revealed to be a separate character (now once again called John Black) who was brainwashed to believe he was Roman, when what would now be the real Roman (once again played by Wayne Northrop) was found on an island where he had been imprisoned by Stefano. Roman was shocked when he found he had been replaced and all his family had accepted John Black as him and John Black had a difficult time accepting he was not really Roman. Roman went back to his life, and he and Marlena tried to live once again as man and wife. After the death of Isabella, in his grief John turned to Marlena for comfort. The two found themselves unable to resolve their feelings for each other from their life together when John believed himself to be Roman. He and Marlena had an affair that resulted in the birth of a daughter, [[Belle Black|Isabella]], named after [[Isabella Toscano]], whom Roman believed to be his own daughter. When he discovered that Marlena and John had an affair and that Belle was not his real daughter, Roman was crushed. In June 1994, Roman leaves town broken and bitter, once again with no family.<ref>{{cite episode|series= Days Of Our Lives |series-link= Days of Our Lives |number = 7304|network=[[NBC]]|credits= [[Ken Corday]] and [[Tom Langan]] ([[Executive producer]]s); [[James E. Reilly]] ([[Head writer]]) |season = 28|date=June 15, 1994 |accessdate= May 22, 2017}}</ref> Later it was said that Roman had died on a mission for the [[ISA (Days of our Lives)|ISA]].\n\n===Late 1990s \u2013 Early 2000s===\nIn 1997 Josh Taylor was brought in as Roman, who was revealed by Stefano DiMera and Kristen Blake to be alive after being exposed to biological warfare while on a deep-cover ISA mission in South America. The cure to his ailment was discovered by John, Hope, and Stefano in a jungle mission that was engineered to drive John and Marlena apart, but in the end had the opposite result.\n\nRoman was \"killed\" during the Salem Stalker Murders in December 2003 during his wedding reception to Kate Roberts, but again was revealed to not really be dead. He lived on the island of Melaswen (New Salem) with every other victim from the Salem Stalker Murders, including Marlena. Eventually, other Salemites arrived on the island, trying to find their \"dead\" loved ones. Some of them went out in the jungle, looking for a way off the island, while the rest remained in \"Salem\" waiting for help. Help finally arrived. Jennifer got to the island, then Hope and Patrick and finally Bo and John. Everyone banded together to get off the island, but Tony wasn't going to make it easy. He created a volcanic eruption, which eventually caused a giant wave. As everyone gathered on makeshift rafts to get off the island, the wave crashed over them. The Coast Guard arrived and managed to rescue some of them, but Roman, Marlena, Jack, and his daughter Cassie were not saved. They were in the clutches of Tony DiMera once again, and he took them to a remote European castle where he held them captive.\n\nWhile in the castle, Tony DiMera (actually Andre DiMera) tormented Roman and Marlena with video of John and Kate growing ever closer back in Salem. Eventually, they believed the two of them had sex, and Roman and Marlena, needing comfort, had sex as well. Shortly thereafter, Jack made his way into their room. They escaped! Through fire and explosions, our group of intrepid Salemites \u2013 Marlena, Roman, Jack and Cassie \u2013 all got out and were on their way home.\n\nOn the ISA jet on the way back to Salem, Roman and Marlena made the decision to not tell Kate and John that they had sex. Marlena was uncomfortable with lying to John, but eventually agreed with Roman. When they arrived back they were shocked to learn that John and Kate had fallen in love and were engaged to be married, but Roman and Marlena still didn't tell the truth about their affair. Soon after they were back Marlena discovered that she was pregnant and that Roman had to be the father, but when the truth came out John wasn't too forgiving. During a fight between Roman and John, Marlena tumbled down the stairs, causing a miscarriage.\n\n===2010s===\nAs the second decade of the 21st century has unfolded, Roman is the commissioner of the Salem police force. After an ill-fated marriage to Kate Roberts, he has remained single and adopted an elder-statesman, back-burner role on the show. He serves primarily as the de facto patriarch of the Brady family and the supervisor and occasional voice-of-reason to junior police officers and ISA agents (with a [[catchphrase]] of sorts developing from his consistent inquiries of \"what da hell\" is going on). He has largely made peace with his past with [[Stefano DiMera]], [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]], and [[Victor Kiriakis]], and remains friends with ex-wives Anna DiMera, [[Marlena Evans]], and Kate Roberts, and is occasionally shown as having a soft spot for all of them. In March 2017 he retired as police commissioner and was seen in a later episode tending bar at the Brady Pub. In 2018 he began working with his friends John Black and Steve Johnson at their private detective business, Black Patch.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/roman.php Roman at '''soap'''central.'''com''']\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of Our Lives characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brady, Roman}}\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional police captains]]\n[[Category:Fictional American police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional police commissioners]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e34:ef60:a6b0:6c39:6708:7e92:8002", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(roman brady)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Brady"}
{"title_page": "List of best-selling books", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{dynamic list}}\n<!--\n\nBE AWARE: many popular published sources from the early 21 century take their facts from this article, or previous versions of it, directly or indirectly. They are therefore not suitable as references, since that would be circular referencing. See the talk page and archives for more information.\n\n-->\nThis page provides '''lists of best-selling individual books and book series''' to date and in any language. ''\"Best selling\"'' refers to the estimated number of copies sold of each book, rather than the number of books printed or currently owned. [[Comic book|Comics]] and [[textbook]]s are not included in this list. The books are listed according to the highest sales estimate as reported in reliable, independent sources. This list is incomplete because there are many books, such as ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'' by [[Alexandre Dumas]], or ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]], that are commonly cited as \"best-selling books\" yet have no reliable sales figures. Similarly, many notable book series that sold very widely are poorly documented ([[Land of Oz]]) or consist of multiple sub-series ([[Tom Swift]]).\n\nAccording to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as of 1995, the [[Bible]] is the best-selling book of all time, with an estimated 5{{nbsp}}billion copies sold and distributed.<ref name=\"guinnessworldrecords\">{{cite web|title=Best selling book of non-fiction|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/best-selling-book-of-non-fiction|publisher=Guinness World Records|accessdate=15 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315025558/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/best-selling-book-of-non-fiction|archivedate=15 March 2015}}</ref>  The ''[[Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung]]'', also known as the ''Little Red Book'', has produced a wide array of sales and distribution figures \u2014 with estimates ranging from 800{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"guinnessworldrecords\"/> to over 6.5 billion printed volumes,<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, ''Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics'', Cambridge University Press 1994, p. 186. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uGZIziWmlmsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=autocratic+tradition+and+chinese+politics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAGoVChMI56TJyKv6yAIViXE-Ch0DEQvm#v=onepage&q=autocratic%20tradition%20and%20chinese%20politics&f=false Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=uGZIziWmlmsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=autocratic+tradition+and+chinese+politics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAGoVChMI56TJyKv6yAIViXE-Ch0DEQvm |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref> with some claiming the distribution ran into the \"billions\"<ref>[[Allen Kent]], Harold Lancour, Jay E. Daily, ''Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science, Volume 22'', CRC Press 1977, p.31. [https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=Encyclopedia+of+Library+and+Information+Science%3A+Volume+22 Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science]</ref> and some citing \"over a billion\" official volumes between 1966 and 1969 alone as well as \"untold numbers of unofficial local reprints and unofficial translations.\"<ref>Alexander C. Cook, ''Mao's Little Red Book: A Global History'', Cambridge University Press 2014, p. xiii [https://books.google.com/books?id=ttjSAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mao%27s+little+red+book:+a+global+history&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIwsfq57T6yAIVSfI-Ch0XggzB#v=onepage&q=mao's%20little%20red%20book%3A%20a%20global%20history&f=false Mao's Little Red Book: A Global History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=ttjSAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mao%27s+little+red+book:+a+global+history&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIwsfq57T6yAIVSfI-Ch0XggzB |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref><ref>Daniel Leese, ''Mao Cult: Rhetoric and Ritual in China's Cultural Revolution'', Cambridge University Press 2013, p. 108 [https://books.google.com/books?id=iqjviY6aFloC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mao+Cult:+Rhetoric+and+Ritual+in+China%27s+Cultural+Revolution&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIzqqJwq_6yAIVgTI-Ch3k6wSv#v=onepage&q=Mao%20Cult%3A%20Rhetoric%20and%20Ritual%20in%20China's%20Cultural%20Revolution&f=false Mao Cult: Rhetoric and Ritual in China's Cultural Revolution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=iqjviY6aFloC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mao+Cult:+Rhetoric+and+Ritual+in+China%27s+Cultural+Revolution&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIzqqJwq_6yAIVgTI-Ch3k6wSv |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref> Exact print figures for these and other books may also be missing or unreliable since these kinds of books may be produced by many different and unrelated publishers, in some cases over many centuries. All books of a religious, ideological, philosophical or political nature have thus been excluded from the below lists of best-selling books for these reasons.\n\nHaving sold more than 500 million copies worldwide,<ref name=\"Forbes\">[https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lml45effkg/j-k-rowling-founder-of-the-harry-potter-empire/ Forbes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825195304/https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lml45effkg/j-k-rowling-founder-of-the-harry-potter-empire/ |date=2017-08-25 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"It and the six subsequent books have now sold 500 million copies worldwide.\" (22 May 2013)</ref><ref>[https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history/ Hybable] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134322/https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history/ |date=2017-09-06 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"Collectively, the seven Harry Potter books have sold nearly 500 million copies since the publication of Harry Potter and the Philosopher\u2019s Stone in 1997, making Harry Potter the bestselling book series of all time.\" (29 April 2012)</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/news/data-show-uk-loves-harry-potter/ The Telegraph] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004015807/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/news/data-show-uk-loves-harry-potter/ |date=2017-10-04 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"More than 500 million copies of the books have been sold worldwide and the series has been translated into 79 languages.\" (26 June 2017)</ref> ''[[Harry Potter]]'' by [[J. K. Rowling]] is the best-selling book series in history. The first [[novel]] in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', has sold in excess of 120 million copies,<ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\">{{cite book|last=Chalton|first=Nicola|author2=MacArdle, Meredith|title=20th Century in Bite-Sized Chunks|publisher=Chartwell Books|year=2017|page=129|isbn=978-0-7858-3510-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eF8HDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=philosopher%27s+stone+120+million&source=bl&ots=xcuvqK2qLp&sig=GFDBLllrb6LEkISCOroWndKwemc&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj69Nu5z-3VAhUyS5oKHftkBawQ6AEITDAL#v=onepage&q=philosopher's%20stone%20120%20million&f=false|accessdate=23 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114001005/https://books.google.com/books?id=eF8HDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=philosopher%27s+stone+120+million&source=bl&ots=xcuvqK2qLp&sig=GFDBLllrb6LEkISCOroWndKwemc&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj69Nu5z-3VAhUyS5oKHftkBawQ6AEITDAL#v=onepage&q=philosopher's%20stone%20120%20million&f=false|archivedate=14 January 2018}}</ref> making it one of the best-selling books of all time. As of June 2017, the series has been translated into 80 languages,<ref>[https://www.jkrowling.com/harry-potter-translated-scots/ J.K. Rowling] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731000042/https://www.jkrowling.com/harry-potter-translated-scots/ |date=2017-07-31 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"20 years after it was first published in the UK in 1997, Harry Potter and the Philosopher\u2019s Stone is to be translated into its 80th language \u2013 Scots!\" (28 June 2017)</ref> placing Harry Potter among history's [[List of literary works by number of translations|most translated literary works]]. The last four books in the series consecutively set records as the fastest-selling books of all time, where the final installment, ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'', sold roughly fifteen million copies worldwide within twenty-four hours of its release.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/53/celebrities08_JK-Rowling_CRTT.html Forbes] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The final one, Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows, has sold 44 million since it was published last July, including 15 million in the first 24 hours.\" (19 December 2008)</ref><ref>[https://www.worldrecordacademy.com/business/fastest_selling_book_world_record_set_by_harry_potter_new_book_70663.htm World Record Academy] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 the seventh and last novel in the series \u2013 sold around 15 million copies worldwide in its first day and set the new world record for the fastest selling book.\" (23 July 2007)</ref> With twelve million books printed in the first U.S. run, it also holds the record for the highest initial print run for any book in history.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6912529.stm BBC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081128201059/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6912529.stm |date=2008-11-28 }} on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The book had a print run of 12 million in the US, compared with 10.8 million for the last book, according to Lisa Holton of the book's US publisher Scholastic.\" (23 July 2007)</ref><ref>[https://www.inshorts.com/news/deathly-hallows-sold-15-mn-copies-in-24-hours-1467645762711 Inshorts] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The final instalment of the Harry Potter series, 'The Deathly Hallows' is recognised by Guinness World Records as 'the fastest selling book of fiction in 24 hours' with a total of 15 million books sold. With 12 million books printed in the first run, it also holds a record for the 'highest initial print run for a fiction book'.\" (4 July 2016)</ref>\n\n==Key==\nFigures are inexact, and methods vary by source; the list is incomplete, since sources are unavailable for many books.\n\n{{legend2|#f9f9f9|Fiction|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n{{legend2|lavender|Nonfiction|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n== List of best-selling individual books ==\n=== More than 100 million copies ===\n<!--\n        Do not add   Don Quixote    or    Tale of Two Cities   without discussing on the talk page, please (see also talk page archives).\n-->\n<!--Fifty Shades of Grey does not qualify as a single volume book. Please see talk page for more details.-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n!Book !! Author(s) !! Original language !! First published !! Approximate sales !! Genre\n|-\n|''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''||[[J. R. R. Tolkien]]|| English || 1954 || 150 million<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levine |first1=Mort |title=\u2018Lord of the Rings\u2019 as you\u2019ve never experienced it |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/04/10/lord-of-the-rings-as-youve-never-experienced-it/ |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |work=The Mercury News |date=April 10, 2015|quote=The three films, based on the Tolkien novels that were written between 1937 and 1949 and sold more than 150 million copies, were filmed in New Zealand\u2019s astonishing forests by director Peter Jackson at a cost of more than $300 million.}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\" /><ref>*\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' is considered by many to be a single book{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}, because it was written and planned by the author to be such. It is written in the preface to many editions that the book is sometimes 'erroneously' referred to as a trilogy, and goes on to state that it is one book in three volumes. Some people consider it to instead be a trilogy or series of three books, because it was originally published as a series of three volumes: ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]'', ''[[The Two Towers]]'', and ''[[The Return of the King]]''. [http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234 ''Waterstone's'']  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928071938/http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234 |date=2007-09-28 }}, Waterstones.com: This move by the publishing house was due largely to post-war paper shortages as well as to minimize the price of the first volume to aid sales.{{failed verification|date=November 2018}}\n*Wagner, Vit. [https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/203389 \"Tolkien proves he's still the king\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309035210/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/203389 |date=2011-03-09 }}, ''[[The Toronto Star]]'', 16 April 2007: In subsequent printings the book has sometimes appeared as a single volume, and in at least one case was split into seven. The figure of 150 million is a 2007 estimate of copies of the full story sold, whether published as one volume, three, or some other configuration.{{failed verification|date=November 2018}} \"Fully one-third of the 150 million copies of The Lord of the Rings sold to date were purchased after the release of the first film in the series.\"</ref>\n| [[fantasy]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]]'' (''O Alquimista'') || [[Paulo Coelho]] || Portuguese || 1988 || 150 million<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/31/alchemist-geneva-brazil-opinions-high-five-paulo-coelho.html Forbes] {{webarchive|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.ca/532/nine-books-sold-more-100-million-copies-and-how-they-compare-my-book |date=2019-10-05 }} on \"High Five With Paulo Coelho\"</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[The Little Prince]]'' (''Le Petit Prince'') ||[[Antoine de Saint-Exup\u00e9ry]] || French || 1943 || 140 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/03/the-little-prince-anniversary/317005/ http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/little-prince-discovery-offers-new-insight-into-classic-book-1.1310195|title='Little Prince' discovery offers new insight into classic book|author=Thomas Adamson (Associated Press)|work=thetimes-tribune.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202095913/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/little-prince-discovery-offers-new-insight-into-classic-book-1.1310195|archivedate=2017-02-02}}</ref>|| [[fantasy]] (picture book)\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'' ||[[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 1997 || 120 million<ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Livingston |first1=Michael |title=Burbank Public Library offering digital copies of first \u2018Harry Potter\u2019 novel to recognize the book\u2019s 20th anniversary |url=https://latimes.com/socal/burbank-leader/news/tn-blr-me-burbank-library-harry-potter-20180831-story.html |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=September 4, 2018|quote=No matter the name, the first Harry Potter book is the best seller of the seven-part series. \u201cSorcerer\u2019s Stone\u201d has sold more than 120 million copies worldwide.}}</ref>|| [[fantasy]], [[Mystery fiction|mystery]]\n|-\n|''[[The Master and Margarita]]'' (''\u041c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440 \u0438 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430'')||[[Mikhail Bulgakov]] || Russian || 1967 || 100 million<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/12/baz-luhrmann-the-master-and-margarita-mikhail-bulgakov-elvis-presley-1202806494/</ref>|| [[fantasy]], [[farce]], [[supernatural fiction|supernatural]], [[Romance novel|romance]], [[satirical novel]]\n|-\n|''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' || [[Lewis Carroll]] || English  || 1865 || 100 million<ref>https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/06/12/alice-lidell-the-girl-that-inspired-alice-in-wonderland-2/</ref>|| [[fantasy novel]]\n|-\n|''[[The Hobbit]]'' ||[[J. R. R. Tolkien]]|| English || 1937 || 100 million<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9555838/The-Hobbit-What-has-made-the-book-such-an-enduring-success.html \"The Hobbit: What has made the book such an enduring success?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113111720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9555838/The-Hobbit-What-has-made-the-book-such-an-enduring-success.html |date=2016-11-13 }}, The Telegraph, 20 September 2012.</ref>|| [[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[And Then There Were None]]''||[[Agatha Christie]]|| English || 1939 || 100 million<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flood |first1=Alison |title=And Then There Were None declared world's favourite Agatha Christie novel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/01/and-then-there-were-none-declared-worlds-favourite-agatha-christie-novel |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>|| [[Mystery fiction|mystery]]\n|-\n|''[[Dream of the Red Chamber]]'' ({{zh||c=\u7d05\u6a13\u5922|labels=no}})||[[Cao Xueqin]]|| Chinese || 1791 || 100 million<ref>{{cite news | title=The five biggest-selling books of all time: in pictures | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8526939/The-five-biggest-selling-books-of-all-time-in-pictures.html?image=4 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | publisher=[[Telegraph.co.uk]] | quote=Approximate sales more than 100m}}</ref>|| [[family saga]]\n\n|}\n\n=== Between 50 million and 100 million copies ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n!Book !! Author(s) !! Original language !! First published !! Approximate sales !! Genre\n|-\n|''[[The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' || [[C. S. Lewis]] || English || 1950 || 85 million<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/books-life/7545438/The-20-greatest-childrens-books-ever.html The Telegraph] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406033817/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/books-life/7545438/The-20-greatest-childrens-books-ever.html |date=2010-04-06 }} on ''The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe'': \"This classic story has sold more than 85 million copies in 29 different languages since its publication in 1950.\" (3 April 2010)</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[She: A History of Adventure]]'' || [[H. Rider Haggard]] || English || 1887 || 83 million<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/invisible-ink-no-309-henry-rider-haggard-a6802696.html The Independent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129221558/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/invisible-ink-no-309-henry-rider-haggard-a6802696.html |date=2016-01-29 }} on ''She'': \"His next novel, She, about a beautiful ageless sorceress, was a smashing success, and by 1965 had sold 83 million copies.\" (3 April 2010)</ref>||[[adventure fiction|adventure]]\n|-\n|''[[The Adventures of Pinocchio]]'' (''Le avventure di Pinocchio'') || [[Carlo Collodi]] || Italian || 1881 || data-sort-value=\"80.1 million\" | >80 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artspecialday.com/9art/2017/10/26/carlo-collodi/|title=Carlo Collodi, il pap\u00e0 del burattino pi\u00f9 conformista della letteratura|language=Italian|publisher=artspecialday.com|date=April 3, 2018|access-date=April 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403234914/http://www.artspecialday.com/9art/2017/10/26/carlo-collodi/|archive-date=April 3, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.repubblicaletteraria.it/Collodi_Pinocchio.htm Repubblica Italiana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428194705/http://www.repubblicaletteraria.it/Collodi_Pinocchio.htm |date=2009-04-28 }} on ''Le Avventure di pinocchio'': \"\u201cThe Adventures of Pinocchio\u201d translated in more of 260 languages.\" (1 July 2001)</ref> || [[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Vardi Wala Gunda]]'' || [[Ved Prakash Sharma]] || Hindi || 1992 || data-sort-value=\"80.1 million\" | >80 million<re