rFARQ.html The Internet Public Library]\n* [http://mulibraries.missouri.edu/specialcollections/mott.htm Frank Luther Mott Collection of American Best Sellers, 1662\u20131945] at the [[University of Missouri]]\n\n{{Books}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Best-Selling Books}}\n[[Category:Top book lists|Best-selling]]\n[[Category:Lists of bestsellers|Books]]\n[[Category:Literature records]]\n", "name_user": "Lauchlanmack", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBetween 50 million and 100 million copies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_best-selling_books"}
{"title_page": "Saint Jhn", "text_new": "{{Short description|American rapper, singer, and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Saint Jhn\n| image            = SAINt JHN 2018.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = John in May 2018\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Carlos St. John\n| birth_date       = August 26, 1986 (age 33)\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| alias            = Ghetto Lenny\n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|record producer|rapper}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|G\u00d8DD COMPLEXx|[[L.A. Reid|Hitco]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*f a l l e n\n*[[Lenny Kravitz]]\n*[[Meek Mill]]\n*[[Wizkid]]\n*[[Marshmello]]\n}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Carlos St. John''', better known by his stage name '''Saint Jhn''' (stylized as '''SAINt JHN'''), is [[Guyanese-American]] rapper, singer, songwriter, and record producer. He released his first album under the Saint Jhn moniker, ''Collection One'', in March 2018. He is best known for his single \"[[Roses (Saint Jhn song)|Roses]]\", initally released in 2016. A 2019 remix of \"Roses\" by Kazakh DJ [[Imanbek]] helped the song become a worldwide hit; it has so far reached the top 40 of the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and topped the charts in Australia, Ireland and the UK. Prior, John wrote songs for a number of acts, including [[Jidenna]], [[Hoodie Allen]], [[Usher (musician)|Usher]], [[Kiesza]], among others.<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite magazine | last=Hyman| first=Dan| title =Young rapper SAINt JHN goes with the flow| magazine =Interview Magazine| date =December 25, 2017 | url =https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/saint-jhn-usher-joey-badass-interview| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> He is a founding member of the G\u00f8dd Complexx music collective.<ref name=\"FADERRoses\">{{cite magazine | last=Starling| first=Lakin| title =How Rapper Saint JHN Learned To Appreciate His Own Gifts| magazine =The FADER| date =October 7, 2016 | url =http://www.thefader.com/2016/10/07/saint-jhn-roses-premiere-interview| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCarlos St. John was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]] and is of [[Guyanese people|Guyanese]] descent. Growing up, he split his time between Brooklyn and Guyana. He began creating music when he was 12 years old and was inspired by his older brother who would rap in the neighborhood with friends. He wrote his first song in his first year of high school while living in Guyana.<ref name=\"FADERRoses\"/><ref name=\"XXLBreak\">{{cite magazine | last=C.M.| first=Emmanuel| title =The Break Presents: SAINt JHN| magazine =XXL| date =November 25, 2016 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/11/the-break-saint-jhn/| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJhn's mother, Sharon Rosita St. John, born in Guyana, was briefly an actress on British television (including the role of Kate Moses in [[Brookside]]) before moving to the United States in the 1980s.\n\n==Career==\nPrior to adopting the Saint Jhn stage name, he performed and wrote using his birth name, Carlos St. John (or Carlos Saint John).<ref name=\"FADERRoses\"/><ref name=\"PPRoses\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Listen to Brooklyn Artist SAINt Jhn's Intense \"Roses\"| publisher =Pigeons & Planes| date =July 22, 2016 | url =https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2016/07/saint-jhn-roses| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, he released an EP (''The St. John Portfolio'') and a mixtape (''In Association'') under his birth name.<ref name=\"PPPortfolio\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Carlos St. John - The St. John Portfolio (EP)| publisher =Pigeons & Planes| date =March 8, 2010 | url =https://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2010/03/carlos-st-john-the-st-john-portfolio-ep| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"PPAssociation\">{{cite news | last=| first=| title =Carlos St. John - In Association (Mixtape)| publisher =Pigeons & Planes| date =December 25, 2010 | url =https://pigeonsandplanes.com/news/2010/12/carlos-st-john-in-association-mixtape| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> Soon after, he was flown to [[Los Angeles]] by music executive, Zach Katz. For two months, he wrote songs for [[Rihanna]], but none of his records were accepted. After returning home, Jhn co-wrote the 2012 Hoodie Allen song, \"No Interruption\".<ref name=\"FADERRoses\"/><ref name=\"DXAlbum\">{{cite magazine | last=Wallace| first=Riley| title =SAINt JHN's Debut Album Took A Lifetime To Create| magazine =HipHopDX| date =March 30, 2018 | url =https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.46369/title.saint-jhns-debut-album-took-a-lifetime-to-create| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref>[[File:SAINt JHN .jpg|thumb|SAINt in Egypt|alt=]]In the following years, Jhn wrote songs for [[Kiesza]], [[Gorgon City]], and [[Nico & Vinz]], among others.<ref name=\"AMCredits\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/carlos-st-john-mn0003315895|title=Carlos St. John - Credits|website=AllMusic |accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref> In 2016, he earned a writer credit for the Usher songs, \"[[Crash (Usher song)|Crash]]\" and \"[[Rivals (song)|Rivals]]\", both of which appeared on the ''[[Hard II Love]]'' album.<ref name=\"DXAlbum\"/> Also in 2016, he released his first song under the moniker, Saint Jhn, entitled \"1999\".<ref name=\"FADER1999\">{{cite magazine | last=Starling| first=Lakin| title =SAINt JHN Lets Us In On His Journey With \"1999\"| magazine =The FADER| date =June 28, 2016 | url =http://www.thefader.com/2016/06/28/saint-jhn-1999-video| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> He followed that with two more songs in 2016, \"[[Roses (Saint Jhn song)|Roses]]\"<ref name=\"HNHHRoses\">{{cite news | last=Smith| first=Trevor| title =SAINt JHN - Roses | publisher =HotNewHipHop| date =July 24, 2016 | url =https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/saint-jhn-roses-new-song.1970748.html| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> and \"Reflex\".<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{cite news | last=Moore| first=Jacob| title =Brooklyn's SAINt JHN Delivers Again With \"Reflex\"| publisher =Yahoo!| date =September 22, 2016 | url =https://www.yahoo.com/news/brooklyns-saint-jhn-delivers-again-170654916.html| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> In October 2016, it was announced that JHN would open up for [[Post Malone]] during a run of shows on the West Coast.<ref name=\"BWW\">{{cite web | title =Rapper SAINt Jhn to Open for Post Malone on West Coast Run| website =Broadway World| date =October 31, 2016 | url =https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Rapper-SAINt-JHN-to-Open-for-Post-Malone-on-West-Coast-Run-20161031| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Jidenna's album, ''[[The Chief (album)|The Chief]]'', was released featuring the song, \"Helicopters / Beware\" which Jhn co-wrote.<ref name=\"DXAlbum\"/> The following month, Jhn released another original track, \"3 Below\".<ref name=\"XXL3\">{{cite magazine | last=Hunter| first=Christopher| title =SAINt JHN Isn't Trying to Be a Hero on New Song \"3 Below\"| magazine =XXL| date =March 7, 2017 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2017/03/saint-jhn-3-below-new-song/| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> In October of that year, he played at two festivals, Rolling Loud and the [[Voodoo Experience]]. He also released another new song, \"Hermes Freestyle\".<ref name=\"XXLHermes\">{{cite magazine | last=C.M.| first=Emmanuel| title =Saint JHN Brags for New Song \"Hermes Freestyle\"| magazine =XXL| date =October 23, 2017 | url =http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2017/10/saint-jhn-hermes-freestyle/| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, Jhn released \"I Heard You Got Too Litt Last Night\".<ref name=\"BBLitt\">{{cite magazine | last=Aniftos| first=Rania| title =Saint JHN Delivers an Ode to the Wild Ones in 'Heard You Got Too Lit Last Night': Exclusive Premiere| magazine =Billboard| date =February 9, 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8097551/saint-jhn-heard-you-got-too-lit-last-night-premiere| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"PFLitt\">{{cite web | last=Balfour| first=Jay| title =SAINt JHN - \"I Heard You Got Too Litt Last Night\"| website =Pitchfork| date =February 13, 2018 | url =https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/saint-jhn-i-heard-you-got-too-litt-last-night/| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> In early March, he released the song, \"Albino Blue\",<ref name=\"PPAlbino\">{{cite news | last=Moore| first=Jacob| title =SAINt JHN Drops \"Albino Blue,\" Plans to Release Debut Album March 30| publisher =Pigeons & Planes| date = March 9, 2018| url =https://pigeonsandplanes.com/music/2018/03/saint-jhn-albino-blue| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref> and on March 30, 2018, his debut album was released. At that time, the already-released songs on the album had accrued 50 million total streams on various platforms. In addition to working on music and a tour in support of ''Collection One'', Jhn was hired by [[Gucci]] as a model for its \"Guilty\" campaign alongside [[Adesuwa Aighewi]].<ref name=\"BBAlbum\">{{cite magazine | last=Lyle| first=Ashley| title =Emerging Rapper SAINt JHN Talks Debut Project 'Collection One' and Being the 'Ghetto Lenny Kravitz'| magazine =Billboard| date =March 30, 2018 | url =https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8269705/saint-jhn-interview-collection-one| accessdate =April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SAINt JHN announces tour in support of debut album 'Collection 1'|url=https://www.axs.com/saint-jhn-announces-tour-in-support-of-debut-album-collection-1-129169|work=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|date=March 28, 2018|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ List of studio 