 (Hoodie Allen EP)|All American]]''\n|rowspan=\"6\"|Co-writer\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Bad Thing\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2014\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kiesza]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Sound of a Woman]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"The Love\"\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Piano\"\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Praying to a God\"\n|2015\n|[[Nico & Vinz]]\n|''Cornerstone''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Doubts\"\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2016\n|[[Gorgon City]]\n|''[[Kingdom (Gorgon City album)|Kingdom]]''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[Crash (Usher song)|Crash]]\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Usher (musician)|Usher]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Hard II Love]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Co-writer, producer\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[Rivals (song)|Rivals]]\"\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Helicopters / Beware\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n|[[Jidenna]]\n|''[[The Chief (album)|The Chief]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Co-writer\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Can't Wait\"\n|[[dvsn]]\n|''[[Morning After (album)|Morning After]]''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://soundcloud.com/saintjhn SAINt JHN on SoundCloud]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jhn, Saint}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:Guyanese musicians]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:African-American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "Lk95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudio albums:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Jhn"}
{"title_page": "1953 Australian Championships", "text_new": "{{TennisEventInfo|1953|Australian Championships|\n| date=9 January \u2013 17 January  \n| edition=41st\n| category=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] (ITF)\n| location=[[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n| venue=[[Kooyong Stadium]]\n| surface=[[Grass court|Grass]]\n| champms={{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]\n| champws={{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]]\n| champmd={{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]\n| champwd={{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]]\n| champxd={{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]]  / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rex Hartwig]] \n| champbs=\n| champgs=\n}}\nThe '''1953 Australian Championships''' was a [[tennis]] tournament that took place on outdoor [[Grass court]]s at the [[Kooyong Stadium]] in [[Melbourne]], Australia from 9 January to 17 January. It was the 41st edition of the Australian Championships (now known as the [[Australian Open]]), the 12th held in Melbourne, and the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournament of the year. American [[Maureen Connolly]] won the women's singles, the first step towards the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] by a woman. Australian [[Ken Rosewall]] won the men's singles title.\n\n==Champions==\n\n===Men's Singles===\n{{main|1953 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]]  6\u20130, 6\u20133, 6\u20134\n\n\n===Women's Singles===\n{{main|1953 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] defeated {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] 6\u20133, 6\u20132\n\n\n===Men's Doubles===\n{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Don Candy]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] 9\u201311, 6\u20134, 10\u20138, 6\u20134 \n \n\n===Women's Doubles===\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mary Bevis Hawton]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Beryl Penrose]] 6\u20134, 6\u20132 \n\n\n===Mixed Doubles===\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rex Hartwig]] defeated {{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ham Richardson]] 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918071711/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/index.html Australian Open official website]\n\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box | before=[[1952 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1952 U.S. National Championships]]| title=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] | years= | after=[[1953 French Championships (tennis)|1953 French Championships]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Australian Open championships}}\n{{1953 in tennis}}\n[[Category:1953 in tennis|Australian Championships]]\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) by year]]\n[[Category:1953 in Australian tennis]]\n[[Category:January 1953 sports events]]\n", "text_old": "{{TennisEventInfo|1953|Australian Championships|\n| date=9 January \u2013 17 January  \n| edition=41st\n| category=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] (ITF)\n| location=[[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n| venue=[[Kooyong Stadium]]\n| surface=[[Grass court|Grass]]\n| champms={{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]\n| champws={{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]]\n| champmd={{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]]\n| champwd={{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]]\n| champxd={{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]]  / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rex Hartwig]] \n| champbs=\n| champgs=\n}}\nThe '''1953 Australian Championships''' was a [[tennis]] tournament that took place on outdoor [[Grass court]]s at the [[Kooyong Stadium]] in [[Melbourne]], Australia from 9 January to 17 January. It was the 41st edition of the Australian Championships (now known as the [[Australian Open]]), the 12th held in Melbourne, and the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournament of the year. American [[Maureen Connolly]] won the women's singles, the first step towards the first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] by a woman. Australian [[Ken Rosewall]] won the men's singles title.\n\n==Champions==\n\n===Men's Singles===\n{{main|1953 Australian Championships \u2013 Men's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]]  6\u20130, 6\u20133, 6\u20134\n\n\n===Women's Singles===\n{{main|1953 Australian Championships \u2013 Women's Singles}}\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] defeated {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] 6\u20133, 6\u20132\n\n\n===Men's Doubles===\n{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lew Hoad]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ken Rosewall]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Don Candy]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mervyn Rose]] 9\u201311, 6\u20134, 10\u20138, 6\u20134 \n \n\n===Women's Doubles===\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] defeated {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Mary Bevis Hawton]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Beryl Penrose]] 6\u20134, 6\u20132 \n\n\n===Mixed Doubles===\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Julia Sampson Hayward|Julia Sampson]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rex Hartwig]] defeated {{flagicon|USA}} [[Maureen Connolly]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ham Richardson]] 6\u20134, 6\u20133 \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918071711/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/index.html Australian Open official website]\n\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box | before=[[1952 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1952 U.S. National Championships]]| title=[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] | years= | after=[[1953 French Championships (tennis)|1953 French Championships]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Australian Open championships}}\n{{1953 in tennis}}\n[[Category:1953 in tennis|Australian Championships]]\n[[Category:Australian Championships (tennis) by year]]\n[[Category:1953 in Australian tennis]]\n[[Category:January 1953 sports events]]\n", "name_user": "Wolbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChampions:Corr. flagicon", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1953_Australian_Championships"}
{"title_page": "Maurice Wetherill", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Maurice Wetherill\n|fullname       = Maurice Charles Wetherill\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|SO|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = Auckland, New Zealand\n|death_date = 1983\n|height         =  5 ft 10 in\n|weight         =  10 st 7 lb\n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|ARL]]\n|year1start     = 1920\n|year1end       = 25\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 24\n|goals1         = 16\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 104 \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1921\n|yearAend       = 25\n|appearancesA   = 24\n|triesA         = 8\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 30\n|teamB               = Auckland Province\n|yearBstart          =1922\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 1\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         =0 \n|pointsB             = 3\n|teamC              = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearCstart          =1924 \n|yearCend            =  30\n|appearancesC        = 20\n|triesC              = \n|goalsC              = \n|fieldgoalsC         = \n|pointsC             = \n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nMaurice Wetherill was a New Zealand rugby league player. He represented New Zealand from 1924 to 1930 and was Kiwi number 156. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = NZRL \u2013 Past Kiwis\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url = https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Early Life===\nMaurice Wetherill was born in [[Auckland]] on January 15, 1928. He was the son of Maurice Charles Wetherill and Mary Ann Wetherill. He had a brother, James Ewart Wetherill, and sister Ivy Pearl Wetherill. He was a plumber by trade and at the time of signing up for [[World War 1]] he was living on Ardmore Road in [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] with his family and working for A.J. Letham. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wetherill, Maurice Charles \u2013 WW1 History Sheet\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===World War 1===\nHe enlisted in the armed forces on February 27, 1918 aged 20. At the time of his service his weight was recorded as 122lb, and his height 5 feet 5 inches. He commenced duty on March 14, 1918 and embarked on the Moeraki on October 11. The ship stopped in [[Sydney]] where the men bound for [[Suez]], [[Egypt]], transhipped to the Malta to complete the journey. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Record \u2013 Maurice Charles Wetherill\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> He was part of the Mounted Rifles \u2013 43rd reinforcements. When he signed up for World War 1 his mother (Mrs. M. A. Wetherill) was listed as living on Ardmore Road in Ponsonby. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Records\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://media.api.aucklandmuseum.com/id/media/v/322529?rendering=original.jpg\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill served in Egypt during the latter part of the war. He returned to New Zealand on board the Hororata. Wetherill was discharged from duty on October 18, 1919 after 1 year and 219 days duty, and 346 days served overseas. He received the [[British War Medal]].\n\n===Playing career===\nAfter returning from the war Wetherill joined the [[City Rovers]] rugby league club where he played for the senior team in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He was small in stature, measuring just 5 feet 5 inches and spent his career playing in the halves or on the wing. In his first season for City he scored 4 tries and kicked 4 conversions including a try on debut.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Opening of the Season/City\u2019s Big Win\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LI| issue=105\n| date = 1920-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200503.2.63\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> In [[1921 Auckland Rugby League season|1921]] the City team won the Monteith Shield by winning the first grade championship. The also won the Roope Rooster trophy after defeating Maritime in the final by 30 points to 14 with Wetherill kicking a conversion.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Victory For City Team/Fast and Exciting Game\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17902\n| date = 1921-10-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19211003.2.114.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-26}}</ref> He made his [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] debut this same season and went on to play 7 matches for them. His first match in an Auckland jersey was against the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 11,000 spectators. Auckland lost the match 22-16.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand V Auckland/Local Team Defeated\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| date = 1921-05-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210523.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> He then played against [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] for the Northern Union Challenge Cup which Auckland won 31-8. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Victory For Local Team/Game Played In Rain\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17848\n| date = 1921-08-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210801.2.107.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref> Wetherill then played 5 further matches all resulting in wins, against Hawkes Bay ((18-3), Wellington (23-21) , West Coast (47-7), Canterbury (38-14), and South Auckland (35-13).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland Beats Hawke\u2019s Bay/Fast Game On Wet Ground\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXIII| issue=17854\n| date = 1921-08-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210808.2.18\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Margin Of Two Points\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17866\n| date = 1921-08-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210822.2.92.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V West Coast/An Easy Victory\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17869\n| date = 1921-09-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210825.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Canterbury/Win For Northerners/Thirty-Nine To Fourteen\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17872\n| date = 1921-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210829.2.93.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V South Auckland/Victory For Local Team/Fast Spectacular Play\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17890\n| date = 1921-09-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210919.2.105.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1922 Auckland Rugby League season|1922]] Wetherill scored 8 tries for City as they again won the first grade championship. Remarkably Wetherill played in 9 matches for Auckland. He scored a try in the 18-28 loss to [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]]. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maori\u2019s Play Well/Defeat of Auckland/28 Points to Eighteen/Fast and Exciting Game/Visitors Show Great Dash\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18096\n| date = 1922-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220522.2.121\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> He then played 3 matches against the touring Australian University side scoring a try in the 3rd match. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Australian University V Auckland/Visitors Win By a Point\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIII| issue=146\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19220622.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Wetherill turned out again for Auckland in a Northern Union Challenge Cup match against Hawkes Bay with Auckland retaining the trophy and Wetherill touching down for another try in a 23-5 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay/Win For the Local Team\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18174\n| date = 1922-08-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220821.2.29\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Prior to this he has been part of the 73-29 thrashing of Cambridge where he crossed the line once. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Cambridge/Won by 73 Points to 29\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18153\n| date = 1922-07-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220727.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> He then went on to play in a loss to South Auckland which saw the [[Rugby League Cup|Northern Union Challenge Cup]] change hands. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Challenge Cup/Win by South Auckland/Fast and Exciting Game/Twenty-One Points to Twenty\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18186\n| date = 1922-09-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220904.2.122\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref> Wetherill was to represent Auckland against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] side where they were well beaten 25-40 with Wetherill kicking a conversion, and he played the same team 4 days later but playing for Auckland Province this time in a 20-21 defeat.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New South Wales Team\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18198\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220918.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =League \"Rep\" Match/New South Wales Team/Game Against Province/Win by 21 Points to 20\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18201\n| date = 1922-09-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220921.2.109\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> His final representative match of the season was an Auckland effort to regain the Northern Union Challenge Cup from South Auckland which was unsuccessful. South Auckland win the match 26-18 and retained the trophy for the summer. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =South Auckland Win/Fast and Open League Play/Auckland Thirteen Defeated/28-16 At the Close\n| page = 6\n| work = Waikato Times| volume=96| issue=15056\n| date = 1922-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19221002.2.66\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1923 Auckland Rugby League season|1923]] he was part of the [[City Rovers]] team which won the first grade championship for the 3rd consecutive season. He played 2 matches for Auckland. The first was against the Auckland Province side which saw the city team win 44-15 with Wetherill scoring a try.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beats Province/In Match of Big Scoring\n| page =9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIV| issue=234\n| date = 1923-10-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19231001.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> While the second match was against South Auckland at [[Carlaw Park]] and on this occasion Wetherill scored twice in a 35-11 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Close of the Season/Auckland 35; S. Auckland 11\n| page =10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LX| issue=18530\n| date = 1923-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19231015.2.170.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nWetherill played 5 matches for Auckland in 1924 and he also made his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut. Wetherill played at halfback in the first test against the touring [[England rugby league team|England]] side. He scored New Zealand\u2019s first try in the corner in a 16-8 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = First League Test/Win for New Zealand\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LV, Issue 183\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240804.2.142\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Unfortunately Wetherill was unable to travel south to play in the remaining test matches which saw New Zealand lose twice and therefore lose the series 1-2.\n\nThe [[1925 Auckland Rugby League season|1925]] season saw Wetherill selected for the New Zealand team to tour [[Australia]]. His weight was listed as 10 stone, 7 pounds which was a significant increase on his weight when he had signed up for the war 5 years earlier. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Fifteen Aucklanders\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 152\n| date = 1925-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250630.2.107\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill played a remarkable 10 matches on the tour of Australia and a further 2 matches for New Zealand against [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] when they toured New Zealand later in the year. While he missed many matches for [[City Rovers]] while on tour he still helped to captain the side to another first grade championship where they edged out [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\nHe played all 3 test matches for New Zealand against the touring England team in 1928. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = New Zealand vs England 1928\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/new-zealand-vs-england-1928/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill also toured Australia again in 1930, playing 4 more matches for New Zealand. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Tour 1930\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kiwis-tour-1930/squad.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Personal Life and Death===\nMaurice Wetherill was married on October 19, 1923 to Stella Jessen. They had one son, Maurice George Wetherill. His son passed away in 1970 aged 47. Maurice\u2019s father who was also named Maurice Charles Wetherill died in 1925 aged 56, his mother Mary died in 1932 aged 55, while his wife Stella died in 1964 aged 60.\n\nMaurice Wetherill died in 1983 aged 85.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wetherill, Maurice}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Maurice Wetherill\n|fullname       = Maurice Charles Wetherill\n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|SO|HB}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = Auckland, New Zealand\n|death_date = 1983\n|height         =  5 ft 10 in\n|weight         =  10 st 7 lb\n|club1          = [[City Rovers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|ARL]]\n|year1start     = 1920\n|year1end       = 25\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 24\n|goals1         = 16\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 104 \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1921\n|yearAend       = 25\n|appearancesA   = 24\n|triesA         = 8\n|goalsA         = 3\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 30\n|teamB               = Auckland Province\n|yearBstart          =1922\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 1\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         =0 \n|pointsB             = 3\n|teamC              = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearCstart          =1924 \n|yearCend            =  30\n|appearancesC        = 20\n|triesC              = \n|goalsC              = \n|fieldgoalsC         = \n|pointsC             = \n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nMaurice Wetherill was a New Zealand rugby league player. He represented New Zealand from 1924 to 1930 and was Kiwi number 156. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = NZRL \u2013 Past Kiwis\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url = https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Early Life===\nMaurice Wetherill was born in [[Auckland]] on January 15, 1928. He was the son of Maurice Charles Wetherill and Mary Ann Wetherill. He had a brother, James Ewart Wetherill, and sister Ivy Pearl Wetherill. He was a plumber by trade and at the time of signing up for [[World War 1]] he was living on Ardmore Road in [[Ponsonby, New Zealand|Ponsonby]] with his family and working for A.J. Letham. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Wetherill, Maurice Charles \u2013 WW1 History Sheet\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===World War 1===\nHe enlisted in the armed forces on February 27, 1918 aged 20. At the time of his service his weight was recorded as 122lb, and his height 5 feet 5 inches. He commenced duty on March 14, 1918 and embarked on the Moeraki on October 11. The ship stopped in [[Sydney]] where the men bound for [[Suez]], [[Egypt]], transhipped to the Malta to complete the journey. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Record \u2013 Maurice Charles Wetherill\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE20834584\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> He was part of the Mounted Rifles \u2013 43rd reinforcements. When he signed up for World War 1 his mother (Mrs. M. A. Wetherill) was listed as living on Ardmore Road in Ponsonby. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Cenotaph Records\n| publisher = Auckland Museum\n| url = https://media.api.aucklandmuseum.com/id/media/v/322529?rendering=original.jpg\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill served in Egypt during the latter part of the war. He returned to New Zealand on board the Hororata. Wetherill was discharged from duty on October 18, 1919 after 1 year and 219 days duty, and 346 days served overseas. He received the [[British War Medal]].\n\n===Playing career===\nAfter returning from the war Wetherill joined the [[City Rovers]] rugby league club where he played for the senior team in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He was small in stature, measuring just 5 feet 5 inches and spent his career playing in the halves or on the wing. In his first season for City he scored 4 tries and kicked 4 conversions including a try on debut. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Opening of the Season/City\u2019s Big Win\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LI| issue=105\n| date = 1920-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200503.2.63\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> In [[1921 Auckland Rugby League season|1921]] the City team won the Monteith Shield by winning the first grade championship. The also won the Roope Rooster after defeating Maritime in the final by 30 points to 14 with Wetherill kicking a conversion.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Victory For City Team/Fast and Exciting Game\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17902\n| date = 1921-10-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19211003.2.114.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-26}}</ref> He made his [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] debut this season and went on to play 7 matches for them. His first match in an Auckland jersey was against the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 11,000 spectators. Auckland lost the match 22-16.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand V Auckland/Local Team Defeated\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| date = 1921-05-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210523.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> He then played in a match against [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington]] for the Northern Union Challenge Cup which Auckland won 31-8. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Victory For Local Team/Game Played In Rain\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17848\n| date = 1921-08-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210801.2.107.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref> Wetherill then played matches 5 further matches all resulting in wins against Hawkes Bay ((18-3), Wellington (23-21) , West Coast (47-7), Canterbury (38-14), and South Auckland (35-13).<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland Beats Hawke\u2019s Bay/Fast Game On Wet Ground\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LXIII| issue=17854\n| date = 1921-08-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210808.2.18\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Wellington/Margin Of Two Points\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17866\n| date = 1921-08-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210822.2.92.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V West Coast/An Easy Victory\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17869\n| date = 1921-09-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210825.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Canterbury/Win For Northerners/Thirty-Nine To Fourteen\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17872\n| date = 1921-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210829.2.93.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V South Auckland/Victory For Local Team/Fast Spectacular Play\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17890\n| date = 1921-09-19\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210919.2.105.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1922 Auckland Rugby League season|1922]] Wetherill scored 8 tries for City as they again won the first grade championship. Remarkably Wetherill played in 9 matches for Auckland. He scored a try in the 18-28 loss to NZ M\u0101ori. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maori\u2019s Play Well/Defeat of Auckland/28 Points to Eighteen/Fast and Exciting Game/Visitors Show Great Dash\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18096\n| date = 1922-05-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220522.2.121\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> he then played 3 matches against the touring Australian University side scoring a try in the 3rd match. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Australian University V Auckland/Visitors Win By a Point\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIII| issue=146\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19220622.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =Universities V Auckland/Australians\u2019 Second Win/Good Game at Domain\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18126\n| date = 1922-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220626.2.105\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> He then played in the Northern Union Challenge Cup match against Hawkes Bay with Auckland retaining the trophy and Wetherill touching down for another try in a 23-5 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay/Win For the Local Team\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18174\n| date = 1922-08-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220821.2.29\n| accessdate = 2019-08-27}}</ref> Prior to this he has been part of the 73-29 thrashing of Cambridge where he crossed the line once. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Cambridge/Won by 73 Points to 29\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18153\n| date = 1922-07-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220727.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> He then went on to play in a loss to South Auckland which saw the Northern Union Challenge Cup change hands. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =League Challenge Cup/Win by South Auckland/Fast and Exciting Game/Twenty-One Points to Twenty\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18186\n| date = 1922-09-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220904.2.122\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref> Wetherill was to represent Auckland against the touring New South Wales side where they were well beaten 25-40 with Wetherill kicking a conversion, and he played the same team 4 days later but playing for Auckland Province this time in a 20-21 defeat.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =New South Wales Team\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18198\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220918.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title =League \"Rep\" Match/New South Wales Team/Game Against Province/Win by 21 Points to 20\n| page = 9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18201\n| date = 1922-09-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220921.2.109\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref> His final representative match of the season was an Auckland effort to regain the Northern Union Challenge Cup from South Auckland which was unsuccessful. South Auckland win the match 26-18 and retained the trophy for the summer. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =South Auckland Win/Fast and Open League Play/Auckland Thirteen Defeated/28-16 At the Close\n| page = 6\n| work = Waikato Times| volume=96| issue=15056\n| date = 1922-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WT19221002.2.66\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1923 Auckland Rugby League season|1923]] he was part of the [[City Rovers]] team which won the first grade championship for the 3rd consecutive season. He played 2 matches for Auckland. The first was against the Auckland Province side which saw the city team win 44-15 with Wetherill scoring a try.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Beats Province/In Match of Big Scoring\n| page =9\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LIV| issue=234\n| date = 1923-10-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19231001.2.134\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> While the second match was against South Auckland at Carlaw Park and on this occasion Wetherill scored twice in a 35-11 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Close of the Season/Auckland 35; S. Auckland 11\n| page =10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LX| issue=18530\n| date = 1923-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19231015.2.170.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\nWetherill played 5 matches for Auckland in 1924 and he also made his New Zealand debut. Wetherill played at halfback in the first test against the touring England side. He scored New Zealand\u2019s first try in the corner in a 16-8 win. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = First League Test/Win for New Zealand\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LV, Issue 183\n| date = 1924-08-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19240804.2.142\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Unfortunately Wetherill was unable to travel south to play in the remaining test matches which saw New Zealand lose twice and therefore lose the series 1-2.\n\nThe [[1925 Auckland Rugby League season|1925]] season saw Wetherill selected for the New Zealand team to tour Australia. His weight was listed as 10 stone, 7 pounds. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Fifteen Aucklanders\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 152\n| date = 1925-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250630.2.107\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill played a remarkable 10 matches on the tour of Australia and a further 2 matches for New Zealand against Queensland when they toured New Zealand later in the year. While he missed many matches for [[City Rovers]] while on tour he still helped to captain the side to another first grade championship where they edged out [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]].\n\nHe played all 3 test matches for New Zealand against the touring England team in 1928. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = New Zealand vs England 1928\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/new-zealand-vs-england-1928/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref> Wetherill also toured Australia again in 1930, playing 4 more matches for New Zealand. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Tour 1930\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kiwis-tour-1930/squad.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n===Personal Life and Death===\nMaurice Wetherill was married on October 19, 1923 to Stella Jessen. They had one son, Maurice George Wetherill. His son passed away in 1970 aged 47. Maurice\u2019s father who was also named Maurice Charles Wetherill died in 1925 aged 56, his mother Mary died in 1932 aged 55, while his wife Stella died in 1964 aged 60.\n\nMaurice Wetherill died in 1983 aged 85.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wetherill, Maurice}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlaying career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Wetherill"}
{"title_page": "Amnesty International UK Media Awards 1997", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Amnesty International UK Media Awards Side Navbar}}\nThe awards were hosted by [[Janet Suzman]] on 18 June 1997 - [[Park Lane Hotel]], [[London]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/>\n\nThere were 7 awards in 6 categories: National Print, Periodicals, Photojournalism, Radio, Television Documentary and Television News. Two awards were issued in the National Print category.\n\nThe overall winner was [[Lindsey Hilsum]], Diplomatic Correspondent for the [[Channel Four News|ITN Channel Four News]] Team for her body of work over through 1996-97 from Rwanda and the former Zaire (Now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]])\n\nThe year's judges for all categories Keiko Itoh,<ref group=lower-alpha name=KeikoItoh/> [[John Mortimer|John Mortimer QC]], Norma Johnston,<ref group=lower-alpha name=NormaJohnston/> Sharon Welch,<ref group=lower-alpha name=SharonWelch/> [[Marc Riboud]], [[Cristina Odone]] and [[James Naughtie]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/><ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 002\"/><ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards INDEX\"/>\n\nFollowing the awards, [[Peter Bottomley]] MP placed an [[Early day motion]] before the UK Parliament requesting that parliament agree \"That this House notes the importance of the Amnesty International Press Awards, ...recognises that links with victims are usually achieved through the Press and broadcasters; and acknowledges that the search for the truth is sometimes a ticket to jail or worse for journalists.\"<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty AIUK EDM 143 Petter Bottomley 18.06.1997\"/>\n\n==Awards 1997==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"centre\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ffdead\" align=\"center\"| '''1997'''\n|-\n! width=20% | Category\n! width=30% | Title\n! width=23% | Organisation\n! width=22% | Journalists\n! width=5% | Refs\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" | '''National Print'''<br />''Joint Winners''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''Articles from Afghanistan'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[The Daily Telegraph]]\n| align=\"center\" | Alex Spillius\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards NATIONAL PRINT\"/><ref name=\"1997 AIUK Award - Alex Spillius Biog 001\"/><br /><br />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cBlack Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[The Observer]]\n| align=\"center\" | David Harrison<br />Melissa Jones\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards NATIONAL PRINT\"/><ref name=\"1997 AIUK AWARDS - \u201cBlack Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine\u201d 001\"/><br /><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Periodicals'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cWhere Girls are Killed for Going to School\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[Marie Claire]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Lara Marlowe]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PERIODICALS\"/><ref name=\"1997 Periodicals \u201cWhere Girls are Killed for Going to School\u201d 001\"/><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Photojournalism'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cThe Highway to Hell\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"center\" | Gary Knight\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PHOTOJOURNALISM\"/><ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Radio'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |  '''\u201cChocolate Soldier from the USA\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" |  BBC Radio South\n| align=\"center\" |  Marc Jobst<br />George Pixley\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards RADIO \"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 002\"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 003\"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 004\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Television<br />Documentary'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cRwanda - The Betrayal\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | Blackstone Pictures for<br />Channel Four Witness\n| align=\"center\" | [[Lindsey Hilsum]]<br />Peter Bate\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION DOCUMENTARY\"/><ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Television<br />News'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cWomen under the Veil\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[Channel 4 News|ITN Channel Four News]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Saira Shah]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION NEWS\"/><ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Amnesty International UK Media Awards Nav Bar}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha|refs=\n\n<ref name=KeikoItoh>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Keiko Itoh was Media Relations Consultant for [[World Bank Group|The World Bank]]</ref>\n\n<ref name=NormaJohnston>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Moram Johnston was Communications Director for Amnesty International UK</ref>\n\n<ref name=SharonWelch>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Sharon Welch was Director of the London Millennium Festival</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<!--  #######          Ref List - Ref List - Ref List          ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html |title=AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS 1997 MARC RIBOUD JOINS PANEL OF JUDGES 29 April 1996 |publisher=Amnesty International UK (AIUK) |date=29 April 1996 |accessdate=18 January 2013 |author=Amnesty UK Press Office |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970530094540/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html |archivedate=30 May 1997 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970530094540/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html|title=AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS 1997 MARC RIBOUD JOINS PANEL OF JUDGES 29 April 1996 |archivedate=30 May 1997 |url-status=dead |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards INDEX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211140852/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/index.html |archivedate=11 February 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty AIUK EDM 143 Petter Bottomley 18.06.1997\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/print/1997-98/143 |title=Early day motion 143 AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS Date tabled: 18.06.1997 |author=Bottomley Peter |journal=House of Commons Business Papers |date=June 1997 |issue=Session: 1997\u201398 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DlHny2FG |archivedate=18 January 2013 |quote=That this House notes the importance of the Amnesty International Press Awards; congratulates David Harrison with Melissa Jones of The Observer for articles about oil companies' role in Columbia, Lara Marlowe of Marie Claire for the investigation in Algeria 'Where Girls are Killed for Going to School', Saira Shah and her colleagues in Channel Four News-ITN for the filming in Kabul under the Taliban 'Women Under the Veil', Lindsey Hilsum with Peter Bate of Blackstone Pictures for Channel 4's Witness programme 'Rwanda-The Betrayed', Marc Jobst and his collegues &#91;sic&#93; for BBC Radio 4's 'Chocolate Soldier from the USA', and photojournalist Gary Knight and Time Magazine International for 'The Highway to Hell'; recognises that links with victims are usually achieved through the Press and broadcasters; and acknowledges that the search for the truth is sometimes a ticket to jail or worse for journalists. |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List  - NATIONAL PRINT         ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards NATIONAL PRINT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/print.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234451/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/print.html |archivedate=29 January 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 AIUK Award - Alex Spillius Biog 001\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alex-spillius/ |title=The Daily Telegraph Journalists Alex Spillius |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group Limited]] |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=18 January 2013 |accessdate=18 January 2013 |archivedate=18 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DlHJSGss |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 AIUK AWARDS - \u201cBlack Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine\u201d 001\">{{cite news | title=Black Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine | work=[[The Observer]] | date=20 October 1996 | author=Harrison, David | last2=Jones | first2=Mellisa}}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List  - PERIODICALS          ######   -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PERIODICALS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/periodicals.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060514014721/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/periodicals.html |archivedate=14 May 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Periodicals \u201cWhere Girls are Killed for Going to School\u201d 001\">{{cite book|author=Clifford Thompson|title=Current Biography Yearbook 2001|url=https://archive.org/details/currentbiography1976thom|url-access=registration|accessdate=18 January 2013|date=1 February 2002|publisher=Hw Wilson Company|isbn=978-0-8242-1016-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/currentbiography1976thom/page/13 13]}}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List -  PHOTOJOURNALISM     ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PHOTOJOURNALISM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/photo.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234355/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/photo.html |archivedate=29 January 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.garyknightphotography.com/evidence-war-crimes-in-congo-1997/photos-pi_23.html |title=Evidence: War Crimes in Congo. 1997 |publisher=Gary Knight |work=garyknightphotography.com Garry Knight Photo Journalist |accessdate=16 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DidSaY7Y |archivedate=16 January 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 002\">{{cite web|url=http://digitaljournalist.org/issue0111/seven15.htm |title=A female Rwandan Hutu refugee lies close to death in the back of an MSF truck after surviving a massacre by rwandan Tutsi guerillas. The refugees had been without food, water or medical aid for several days. |publisher=The Digital Journalist |work=Seven by VII |author=Knight, Gary |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DlaX0JhL |archivedate=18 January 2013  }}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List  - RADIO          ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards RADIO \">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/radio.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234242/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/radio.html |archivedate=29 January 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 001\">{{cite news | title=High in the saddle with guitar string twanging | work=[[The Independent]] | date=16 March 1997}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 002\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/radio.html |title=BBC Radio South \"Chocolate Soldier from the USA\" produced by Marc Jobst, presented by George Pixley |accessdate=18 January 2013 |author=Amnesty International UK (AIUK) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234242/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/radio.html |archivedate=29 January 2006 |quote=In England, African Americans and Latinos made up 100% of the people executed for rape. No white soldier was executed for rape in England. And an analysis of that value seems to indicate that they executed people who were the lowest of the low in terms of their social characteristics, not because of the crime that was committed. I know of an instance where a white soldier was convicted of raping a 16-year-old girl, he was a commander and ended up getting 30 days. He was also very articulate, he had a very good defence and he was in a crucial position that the command could not afford to lose. It had nothing to do with justice at all, but it has to do with maintaining discipline The US army was very concerned that black soldiers particularly did not learn to act differently when they were away from home and race was one way they could be reminded of their place. |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 003\">{{cite AV media| title=Chocolate Soldier From the USA | others=[[BBC]] | publisher=WNKU - NKU's National Public Radio station | date=26 February 1999 |url=http://caa.nku.edu/programreview/docs/sociologyreview05.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609201126/http://caa.nku.edu/programreview/docs/sociologyreview05.pdf | archivedate=9 June 2010 | quote=US Broadcast}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 004\">{{cite book|title=Amnesty: The Journal of the British Section of Amnesty International, Issues 59-86 |year=1993|publisher=The Section|page=79|quote=Black soldiers who fought in the European theatre of operations in World War II were treated shamefully - and still are, said Marc Jobst }}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List  - TELEVISION DOCUMENTARY          ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION DOCUMENTARY\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvdoc.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234520/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvdoc.html |archivedate=29 January 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 001\">{{cite episode|title=Rwanda - The Betrayal |series=Witness |network=[[Channel 4]] |date=16 May 1996 |quote=Library Synopisis \"The atrocities in Rwanda two years ago, when members of the Hutu majority slaughtered thousands of men, women and children from the Tutsi minority, are thought to be the worst committed since the Nazi holocaust. The programme examines how this could be allowed to happen in a country where 70% of the population is Catholic. The programme talks to the survivors and asks why the churches were unable to provide sanctuary for the terrified people who fled there for protection. Also examines the moral confusions faced be people confronting personal disaster, including a Hutu woman whose own brother took part in the murder of her Tutsi husband and children\" |url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/549764?view=synopsis |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DlUlrgQ9?url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/549764?view=synopsis |archivedate=18 January 2013  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 002\">{{cite video | url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvdoc.html | title=Channel Four Witness \"Rwanda - The Betrayal\" presented by Lindsey Hilsum produced and directed by Peter Bate of Blackstone Pictures | publisher=[[Channel 4]] | date=16 May 1996 | people=[[Lindsey Hilsum]] | medium=Video | location=Rwanda | quote=\"I think the ethnic element was at play. In the country, according to official propaganda it was Tutsis who had attacked the Hutus, for certain. So there were some even among the priests and perhaps the bishops who believed that it was legitimate defence to kill people of the other ethnic groups.\"...\"How can they be good Christians, those who destroyed the church?  They killed people inside the church, then came to pray in it. People fled to the church. They thought they would be saved but it became the worst place to be. It was where most people died.\" | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19971011093034/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvdoc.html | archivedate=11 October 1997}}</ref>\n\n<!--  #######          Ref List  - TELEVISION NEWS          ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION NEWS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvnews.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060129234311/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/tvnews.html |archivedate=29 January 2006  }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 001\">{{cite AV media | url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist//ITN/1996/10/28/BSP281096024/ | title=Afghanistan: Taliban Regime {{ndash}} Ref: BSP281096024 | others=Saira Shah | publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV Networks]], [[ITN]] | date=28 October 1996 | quote='Hunger itself is a weapon. My children cling to me and beg for food. They'd be better off dying instantly from a rocket.'  Since the Taliban came to power, she hasn't been able to leave her home to search for food, because she says she cannot obey the demands that she must be covered from head to foot.  'They don't care about my problems. A full length veil costs twelve pounds. I can't afford that. I can't even afford food.'  At this orphanage boys still receive a basic education but since the Taliban arrived the girls remain locked away on the top floor of the building. Visitors are shown around the boys areas only.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 002\">{{cite AV media | url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist//ITN/1996/10/28/BSP281096036/ | title=Afghanistan: Taliban Regime {{ndash}} Ref: BSP281096036 | others=Saira Shah | publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV Networks]], [[ITN]] | date=28 October 1996 | quote=Channel Four smuggled the camera inside the girls floor. There are 75 of them here crammed into a couple of rooms. Facilities are basic. The girls lessons have been stopped. They've spent the last 4 weeks in their dormitories.  'We used to go outside to play, but since the Taliban came we can't,' says this girl.  Only 2 female staff members have braved the Taliban to come into work. They're angry at the conditions here.}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.amnesty.org.uk Amnesty International UK (AIUK) website]\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6DWwaWA7k?url=http://www.amnesty.org.uk/content.asp?CategoryID=10058 Amnesty International UK Media Awards at the AIUK Website]\n* [https://www.amnesty.org/ Amnesty International Website]\n\n[[Category:British journalism awards]]\n[[Category:1997 awards in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Amnesty International UK Media Awards Side Navbar}}\nThe awards were hosted by [[Janet Suzman]] on 18 June 1997 - [[Park Lane Hotel]], [[London]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/>\n\nThere were 7 awards in 6 categories: National Print, Periodicals, Photojournalism, Radio, Television Documentary and Television News. Two awards were issued in the National Print category.\n\nThe overall winner was [[Lindsey Hilsum]], Diplomatic Correspondent for the [[Channel Four News|ITN Channel Four News]] Team for her body of work over through 1996-97 from Rwanda and the former Zaire (Now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]])\n\nThe year's judges for all categories Keiko Itoh,<ref group=lower-alpha name=KeikoItoh/> [[John Mortimer|John Mortimer QC]], Norma Johnston,<ref group=lower-alpha name=NormaJohnston/> Sharon Welch,<ref group=lower-alpha name=SharonWelch/> [[Marc Riboud]], [[Cristina Odone]] and [[James Naughtie]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/><ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 002\"/><ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards INDEX\"/>\n\nFollowing the awards, [[Peter Bottomley]] MP placed an [[Early day motion]] before the UK Parliament requesting that parliament agree \"That this House notes the importance of the Amnesty International Press Awards, ...recognises that links with victims are usually achieved through the Press and broadcasters; and acknowledges that the search for the truth is sometimes a ticket to jail or worse for journalists.\"<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty AIUK EDM 143 Petter Bottomley 18.06.1997\"/>\n\n==Awards 1997==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"centre\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ffdead\" align=\"center\